11. O-O{ White does the same. From a strategic viewpoint, white has more active pieces due to a lead in development, whereas black has more space due to the pawn on  c4 . Our strategic goal should be to develop our pieces as quickly as possible whereas white will look to exploit their lead in development. }
11. Re8{ Stopping the potential  e4  breaks and bringing a new piece into the game. }
12. Nd2{ The main line. White controls the  e4  square square with the knight. This works now because white has completed development. }
12. g6{ Creating an escape square and gaining a tempo. }
13. Bxd7{ Giving up the bishop pair to stop black from developing. Black is forced to take back with the knight, restricting the development of  c8 -bishop. }
13. Nxd7{ Forced. We have won the bishop pair at the cost of development. Our plan is to somehow develop the  c8 -bishop or gain space with  b5 . }
14. Rae1{ This is weaker. The  f1  rook is misplaced. Although this is not relevant for openings, I think it's a good point to add in general. There are many situations when both of your rooks are eyeing for the same (in this case, the  e1  square.) What should you do in such situations? The rule of thumb is to usually check which rook will be worse on their initial square and bring them to the intended square. In practical terms, the rook on  f1  isn't doing much, even after the  e4  break. The  a1  rook could be placed on  c1  or  d1 , which would be doing a better job than the rook on  f1 . This is why  Rfe1  is stronger. }
14. b5{ Typical. We gain space and prepare ... Bb7 , developing our worst placed piece. This can be followed up with ... Bf8 - b4 , rolling over the queenside. }
15. f3{ Looking to open up the position with  e4 . }
15. Bb7{ We have developed all of our pieces and have a huge spacial edge.  e4  makes the  d4  pawn weak. Black is clearly dominating the board. }
