11. Re8{ Apart from the main line with  12.Nd2 , white has plenty of alternatives. We will be covering all the 12th move sidelines in this chapter. }
12. Rfb1{ The most challenging sideline. This is far from the main option, but I find it to be more challenging than 12.Nd2. White's idea is that after  Bxc3 , they can recapture with the queen. After  Qxc3  ... bxc3 , white's rook is on the active b-file. Very deep and not going to be played by someone who isn't very well prepared. }( {  A)  }12.Rae1? { unnecessarily brings the rook into a pin. Black can exploit this with }12...Ne4∓ { followed by the typical  ...Nxc3  or  ..Nf6 / Nb6 . } )( {  B)  }12.Rfe1 Ne4⩱ { is quite similar to the  Rae1  line. } )( {  C)  }12.Bh4!? { getting out of attack with  Ne4 . However, this wastes crucial time which we can exploit with }12...g6! { forcing a decision with the light-squared bishop. }13.Bh3 ( { ( }13.Bxd7 Nxd7 { and we are completely alright. The typical plan of ... Nb6 - Bxc3 - Be6  works just fine). } )13...Ne4 { , }13.Nxe4 { runs into }13...Rxe4! { we don't have to even spoil our pawn structure here. } )
12. Bxc3{ We don't have any other choice. }
13. Qxc3{ The correct recapture. }( 13.bxc3 { is inferior. We can play the typical }13...Ne4 { followed by  ...Nb6 . } )
13. Qa6{ A very important subtlety.  Qxc3  ran into ... bxc3 , with ideas of  a4 - a5  looming. After ... Qa6 , we have a couple of plans: one is to push  b5 , gaining space. The other plan is to play ... Ne4 , putting pressure on the queen and the  g5 -bishop.    Another point to note is that the bishop on  f5  is unprotected, and we have tactical ideas like ... Ne5  up our sleeves! }
14. b3{ White tries to eliminate black's  c4  pawn, which is responsible for black's space advantage and restricting white's queenside pieces. }
14. Ne5{ The brilliant point. We are able to eliminate our inactive bishop on  c8 . }
15. Bxc8
15. Nxf3+
16. gxf3
16. Raxc8{ We have ruined white's kingside structure and developed all of our pieces. }
