15. dxe5
15. Bxf5{ A very important point to note is that the  b1  rook is under attack! }
16. exf6{ The only challenging try. Moving the rook away would run into ... Ne4 . }
16. Bxb1
17. Rxb1
17. Qxa2{ With a double attack on  b3  and the  b1 -rook. }
18. Qe1{ Defending the  b1 -rook. }
18. cxb3{ Black's passed pawn look extremely scary. }
19. fxg7{ Trying to open up the kingside. }
19. a5{ We aren't concerned about the pawn on  g7 ! In fact, it serves as a shield against white's attack on the kingside, as capturing one's own pieces is not permitted. We can safely mobilize our queenside majority and advance our pawns. White's position is quite critical, and finding a defensive strategy is far from intuitive. }
20. Bf6{ Defending the  g7 -pawn and looking to create some mating ideas with  Nd4 - f5 - h6 . }
20. a4{ We don't care! White can keep the balance with  Rb2 , but black's position is quite easy to play. It's good to know that the knight moves don't work. }
21. Rb2
21. Qa3{ Followed by ... Ra6 / Re6 , with an extremely complicated position where I prefer black. }
