( { In this chapter, we will be dealing with white's alternatives after }6.e3 c5 { and }7.cxd4 exd4 { . } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Nbd7
5. Bg5
5. Bb4
6. e3
6. c5
7. cxd5{ We will be covering all the options except  8.Bd3  here. }
7. exd5
8. Rc1{ I wouldn't have included this, but Ding played it once in 2011. This move doesn't appeal to me much because the kingside remains fairly underdeveloped. }( 8.Qc2 { , developing the queen first, is also a possibility, but after }8...Qa5 { , White doesn't have a great alternative to }9.Bd3 { , which transposes into the lines discussed in Chapters 2 & }{ 3. } )
8. c4{ This is the right time to gain space. White can't break open with  b3  due to the pin along the  a5 - e1  diagonal. }
9. Be2{ This move develops a piece and aims to castle. Our reply is the usual one. }
9. Qa5{ Putting pressure on  c3 . }
10. O-O
10. O-O{ We have all the standard plans of ... Bxc3 - Ne4  or ... b5  at our disposal. The Bishop on  e2  is misplaced. Black is slightly better. }
