5. Bg5
5. Bb4
6. a3{ Directly attacking the bishop immediately might be a weaker option. Instead, we can take advantage of the vulnerable  c4  pawn with our next move. }
6. Bxc3+
7. bxc3
7. dxc4{ As we observed in chapter one, the knight on  d7  can be highly useful when we are contemplating moves like ... dxc4 . We have both ... b5  and ... Nb6  ideas in mind, ready to put pressure on the position. }
8. e4{ With a dual threat of  e5  &  Bxc4 . }
8. h6{ Looking to exploit the weak pawn on  e4 . }
9. Bxf6{ giving up the Bishop pair can't be great. }
9. Nxf6
10. Qb1{ the only move to defend  e4  and prevent  b5  simultaneously. }
10. b6{ We look to develop as usual. }
11. Bxc4
11. Bb7{ A good point to stop. White's pawn structure is slightly weak, and our pieces are quite active. We are going to follow up with castling and  c5 , looking to attack white's central pawns. }
