( { We'll be covering white's 6th move alternatives after }5.Bg5 Bb4 { in this chapter. The real main alternative seems to be }6.cxd5 { , with a possible transposition to the main lines after }6.e3 c5 { . } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Nbd7
5. Bg5
5. Bb4
6. cxd5( 6.Bxf6 { with the idea that if black's knight captures the bishop on  f6  }6...Nxf6 { , this is met by }7.Qa4+ { . However, black doesn't provide this opportunity to white and instead disrupts white's queenside pawn structure first with }6...Bxc3+ { . After }7.bxc3 { and }Nxf6 { , black is in a very comfortable position. Black can play  ...O-O  followed by  ...c5  or  ...b6 - Bb7  next. } )
6. exd5{ Only move to win back the material. }
7. Rc1{ This is a very popular alternative too. White develops a fresh piece, and prepares  a3 . }
7. c6{ One of the variations where black has to opt for the Carlsbad structure. With white's rook on  c1 , playing ... c5  was very risky. However, black can still proceed with ... Qa5  as usual. }
8. e3
8. Qa5{ With the typical idea of ... Ne4 , white has a couple of ways to react against this plan. }
9. Qb3{ Defends the knight on  c3 , but black can still continue the game as planned. }
9. Ne4{ Improving our knight's position. White has to spend some time to defend the bishop now. }
10. Bf4
10. c5{ Trying to gain space and exploit the pin on  a2 . The  d5 -pawn is untouchable due to the attack on the  c3 -knight. }( 10.-- c4 11.Qc2 Qxa2 { is a big threat. } )
