6. cxd5( 6.Bxf6 { with the idea that if black's knight captures the bishop on  f6  }6...Nxf6 { , this is met by }7.Qa4+ { . However, black doesn't provide this opportunity to white and instead disrupts white's queenside pawn structure first with }6...Bxc3+ { . After }7.bxc3 { and }Nxf6 { , black is in a very comfortable position. Black can play  ...O-O  followed by  ...c5  or  ...b6 - Bb7  next. } )
6. exd5{ Only move to win back the material. }
7. Nd2{ This is a tricky sideline, even tried by yours truly. White is threatening  Nxd5 , aiming to prevent both the ... c5  and ... Qa5 - Ne4  plans. Black is forced to adopt a Carlsbad structure. The downside for white is that they are making a move with an already developed piece, which results in a slight lead in development for black. }
7. c6{ Defending  d5 . }
8. e3{ White looks to finish development with  Bd3  &  O-O . }
8. Nf8{ Preparing ... Ng6  & ... h6 . We are looking to encircle the  g5  bishop. We can afford to lose some time since white spent some time on  Nd2  too. Karma. }
9. Bd3{ Bringing the final minor piece into the game. }
9. Ng6{ Consistent with our plan. We are ready to play  h6 . }
10. O-O{ Securing the king. We have to be careful with our next move. }
10. O-O{ Black castles first before striking with  h6 . Black's bishop on  b4  is not in trouble anymore. White has a few alternatives here. }( { The move }10...h6 { runs into }11.Bxf6 Qxf6 12.Nxd5 { oops now }13...cxd5 13.Qa4+ { , which results in white winning material. } )
11. f4{ Most critical. White gains space and threatens  f5 , making it awkward for our knight on  g6 . Compared to the normal stonewall lines, white's bishop is quite well placed on  g5 . }
11. h6{ We can continue with our plan. White loses the bishop pair. }
12. Bxf6{ The best move. White stops us from attacking  e3  easily. }
12. Qxf6{ Forced. We are ready to play ... Nh4  or ... Re8  next. }
13. f5{ White continues with their plan to gain space and attack our kingside. }
13. Qg5{ A very important intermezzo. We activate our Queen and look to attack both  f5  and  g2  with  Nh4 . }( 13...Nh4 { is met with }14.Qh5 { with the threat of  Rf4 . Our knight on  h4  is in trouble. } )
14. Qe2( { Defending the crucial }e3 { pawn }14.fxg6 { ran into }14...Qxe3+ 15.Kh1 Qxd3-+ { winning material and the pair of bishops. } )
14. Nh4{ Keeping the knight active and making threats continuously. }
15. Nf3{ White looks to trade our active knight on  h4  with their inactive knight. }
15. Qh5{ Important novelty. We want to exchange on our terms.  Qh5  forces white to exchange, since we are threatening  Nxf5 . }( 15...Nxf3+ { allows white to improve their position with }16.Rxf3 { White has ideas like  Qf2 - Rg3  in the air. We don't want to allow this without any concessions. } )
16. Nxh4{ Exchanging the active knight. }
16. Qxh4{ When compared to the line with  Nxf3 , this line looks a lot better. White's rook is still on  f1  & the Queen is less vulnerable on  h4 . }
17. f6{ This is premature. We can activate our worst-placed piece now. }
17. Bg4
18. Qd2{ Getting out of the attack. }
18. Bd6{ Both of our Bishops and the Queen are active. We are putting some pressure against the white's pawns. }
