( { We'll be covering white's 6th move alternatives after }5.Bg5 Bb4 { in this chapter. The real main alternative seems to be }6.cxd5 { , with a possible transposition to the main lines after }6.e3 c5 { . } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Nbd7
5. Bg5
5. Bb4
6. cxd5( 6.Bxf6 { with the idea that if black's knight captures the bishop on  f6  }6...Nxf6 { , this is met by }7.Qa4+ { . However, black doesn't provide this opportunity to white and instead disrupts white's queenside pawn structure first with }6...Bxc3+ { . After }7.bxc3 { and }Nxf6 { , black is in a very comfortable position. Black can play  ...O-O  followed by  ...c5  or  ...b6 - Bb7  next. } )
6. exd5{ Only move to win back the material. }
7. Qc2{ Makes a lot of sense too. White is preparing  e3  and hoping to get a comfortable position with  e3 - Bd3 . }
7. c5{ We react in the typical fashion of striking the centre. }
8. dxc5{ The main alternative. White creates an isolated pawn on  d5 . }( 8.e3 { transposes to chapter  two  and three. }{ (chapter:4) } )
