14. Rd1{ Attacking our pawn on  d5 . }
14. a5{ We continue with our typical plan. }
15. Qd4{ We're moving the queen out of attack while keeping the  c5 -pawn defended. This move is superior to  Qb2 , as it enables White to keep an eye on our pawn on  d5 . }
15. Nxd6{ We reply in the typical fashion by chopping off white's active bishop. }
16. cxd6{ We can defend the  d5 -pawn and attack the  d6 -pawn simultaneously now! }
16. Nf6{ This will be followed by ... Qxd6  on the next move. White can't maintain control of the  d6 -pawn for long. The position is balanced, with white having slightly more active pieces, but us having a superior pawn structure. Next, we'll play  ...Qd6 , followed by completing our development with either  ... Bd7 /Bg4  and then  ...Rac8 . }
