( { Chapter 6 brings us to the end of the  Bg5  lines. In this chapter, we cover the other major setup,   }5.cxd5 exd5 6.Bf4 { . This was recommended by Shankland in his Chessable course on  1.d4 , making this chapter quite important. As you'll see later in the chapter, the analysis merely begins where Shankland stops. I believe I have been able to effectively neutralize Shankland's suggestion. } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Nbd7
5. cxd5
5. exd5
6. Bf4{ The starting point of this chapter. Strategically speaking, the bishop is a bit inferior on  f4  than it would be on  g5 . It doesn't exert pressure on  f6  or  d5 . However, it has his own merits too. The main one being that the bishop wouldn't be under fire after ... h6 / g5  or ... Ne4 . That being said, I still want to fight for initiative here. }
6. Bb4{ Not the main move, but the most exciting. We are again aiming to play the typical ... c5 - Qa5  or ... Ne4  plans. }
7. e3{ The main move. White ignores our threats and continues to develop. }
7. Ne4{ We improve the knight's position as usual. Our plan is to either play ... c5 - Qa5  or to gain space on the other flank with ... g5 . }
8. Qc2{ Defending the  c3 -knight in the most natural way. This is what Shankland recommends too. }
8. g5{ We have already seen this idea couple of times here. We play ... g5  to gain space and harass the pieces on  f4  and  f3 . The drawback of this is we slightly weaken our kingside. Therefore, look to be energetic with our play and allow to develop their pieces easily. }
9. Bg3{ Has been played a few times too. White retreats without any central confrontation. }
9. h5{ Keeping up with the spirit of the course. We want to crush our opponent with our activity. How often do you see ... h5 - g5  on move 9 as black! White has three main options here. }
10. Bd3{ This is quite interesting. White loses a piece, but has good compensation. }
10. h4{ We are obviously trying to win the  g3 -bishop. }
11. Bxe4{ White wins a pawn with check. }
11. dxe4
12. Qxe4+
12. Kf8{ White wins a pawn but the  g3 -bishop is very close to being trapped. The best way to sacrifice the piece is by playing the next move. }
13. Be5{ With the idea that our king is slightly exposed after we win the bishop. We have no choice now. }
13. f6{ Trapping the bishop. }
14. Nxg5{ Sacrificing the piece in the most efficient way. }
14. Nxe5{ we could also started with  Bxc3 + }
15. dxe5
15. Bxc3+{ one way or other, we would land by force in the position after }
16. bxc3
16. fxg5{ Black is up a piece for 2 pawns, but our king is extremely weak. Additionally, the pawn on  e5  is quite dangerous. That being said, a piece is a piece. As far as I can see, there's just a single practical game in this variation. }
17. f4{ looking to open up the f-file or pushing  f5 . This is already a novelty. }
17. Kg7{ We get out of the f-file regardless. }
18. f5{ white is preparing  f6  and stopping us from playing  Bd7 - Bc6 . }
18. Bxf5{ giving up the bishop for activity. }
19. Qxf5
19. Rf8
20. Qe4
20. Qe7{ And things have changed. We are a pawn down, but white's king lacks a safe space. White's pawn are quite fragile. We have no issues whatsoever. }
