7. Ne4{ We improve the knight's position as usual. Our plan is to either play ... c5 - Qa5  or to gain space on the other flank with ... g5 . }
8. Qc2{ Defending the  c3 -knight in the most natural way. This is what Shankland recommends too. }
8. g5{ We have already seen this idea couple of times here. We play ... g5  to gain space and harass the pieces on  f4  and  f3 . The drawback of this is we slightly weaken our kingside. Therefore, look to be energetic with our play and allow to develop their pieces easily. }
9. Be5{ The most played option and the line which Shankland recommends. White wants to force ... f6  before going back to  g3 . }
9. Nxe5{ We don't want to weaken our position after ... f6 . So we just win the bishop pair instead. }
10. Nxe5{ White improves their knight, just like our knight on  e4 . This is where Shankland stops, claiming white has an advantage after  Bd3  and  O-O . I would like to strongly object! }( 10.dxe5 { creates an unnecessary weakness on  e5  }10...Qe7 { (with the threat of  ...g4  &  ...Qe5 ). } )
10. c6{ We support our slightly vulnerable  d5 -pawn as well as we stop all  Qa4 + nonsense. }
11. Bd3{ The most ambitious and following in Shankland's footsteps. White develops the piece to the most active square. }
11. f6{ We force the knight back to  f3 . }
12. Nf3{ Forced. }
12. Qe7{ Defending the  e4 -knight with a fresh piece. Strategically speaking, we have the bishop against a lead in development for white and very slightly ruined pawn structure. However, as you'll see, our moves are very easy to make. We just want to roll our pawns :) }
13. a3{ again, white forces to give up the double bishop advantage. This is the comp's top choice. }
13. Bxc3+{ We need to give up the bishop pair. }
14. bxc3
14. Nd6{ Stopping white from eliminating the weakness with  c4  without giving up the active bishop.     Our plan is quite simple: play ... Be6 , castle on the queenside and roll pawns on the kingside with ... h5 - h4 - g4 - g3 .     This is already a novelty. The lines are not forcing by any means from this onwards, but they represent a good chunk of our ideas. }
15. Nd2{ White looks to improve their knight and get rid of any ... g4  ideas. }
15. Be6{ We develop our piece and prepare ... O-O-O . }
16. O-O{ Finishing development. }
16. O-O-O{ We do the same. We are ready to launch our assault on kingside with ... h5 . }
17. a4{ White wants to poke holes near our king too. }
17. h5{ We follow our typical plan. }
18. a5{ White gains space on the Queenside. }
18. h4{ and we gain on the kingside. White has 2 possible plans here; to attack without  a6  or to include  a6 . }
19. Rab1{ keeping the option of pushing  a6  in hand. }
19. Kb8{ ruinning away with the king to  a8 .  a6  is always met safely with  b6 . The only real try seems to be }
20. Nb3{ with the intention of  Nc5 , putting pressure on  b7 . }
20. Ka8{ we secure our king and are ready to meet }
21. Nc5{ with }
21. h3{ poking some weaknesses first }
22. g3
22. Bg8{ An instructive point. We can eliminate our passive bishop for the active one on  d3 . We are completely fine. }
