6. b5( { We don't want to give up the  c4 -pawn so easily. Something like }6...Be7 { would be met by }7.Bxc4 { , allowing white to control the centre completely. } )
7. e5{ Keeping the e-pawn on the board. }
7. Nd5{ The knight is best placed in the centre. }
8. Nxb5{ Winning the pawn back and threatening the obvious ... Bxc4 . }
8. N7b6{ The first key position arises after  a3 . Black has a weak pawn on  c4 , but in return, gains excellent outposts for their knights and exploits the light-squared weaknesses in white's position.     White's idea is to capture the  c4  pawn, while black aims to repair the pawn structure with moves like .... Bb7 - c5 . Additionally, black would like the knight on  b5  to return to  c3 , enabling them to capture on  c3  and play ... c5 .     This approach helps diminish white's attack against the  c4 -pawn and opens up the diagonal for black's bishop on  b7 . }
9. Nd2{ Principled. White aims to win the pawn without giving up the bishop pair. However, the drawback is that white makes a move with an already developed piece. }( 9.Nc3 { is what we want to get in the ideal world. }9...Nxc3 10.bxc3 c5 { is our ideal setup. The bishop will be a monster on  b7 , and we are able to eliminate the doubled pawns after  cxd4 . The  d5 -square is a juicy outpost. } )
9. Qd7{ Putting pressure on the  b5 -knight. }
10. Nxc4( { The tactical point white was relying on. }10.Qxb5 { runs into }10...Nd6 { , winning material. Nevertheless, we can improve our position still. } )
10. Ba6{ Increasing pressure on the loose pieces. We bet on activity of our pieces for the lost pawn. White has a couple of ways to react. }
11. Nxb6{ The most natural. White trades the loose knight but helps us improve our pawn structure in return. }
11. axb6{ The pawns are not isolated anymore. White needs to take a decision regarding the  b5  knight again. }
12. Nc3{ is met by }
12. Nxc3
13. bxc3
13. Bxf1{ White can't castle anymore. }
14. Kxf1
14. Ra5{ With excellent compensation. We can play ... Be7 , ... O-O  next. This can be followed by ... Rfa8  or ... b5 , fixing the pawns on  c3  &  a3 . }
