{ The 11th and final chapter on the Manhattan system covers 5.Qc2, one of the most challenging and underrated options for white. However, I believe I managed to find a good novelty which effectively neutralizes white's idea. }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Nbd7
5. Qc2{ The starting point of this chapter is  Qc2 , a very deep and extremely tricky move. }( { The idea is that black cannot play }6...Bb4 { effectively anymore due to }7.a3 Bxc3 8.Qxc3! { where black has given up the bishop pair without spoiling white's pawn structure on the queenside. After spending numerous hours and rewriting a full chapter because I wasn't satisfied with the previous suggestion, I recommend challenging white's center immediately. } )
5. c5{ Exploiting the fact that the  d4  pawn is slightly vulnerable after the Queen moves to  c2 . What I like most about this move that it is the most direct & strategically principled move. The alternatives have their own problems. }( 5...c6 6.e3 { transposes to Meran, which is outside the scope of this course. } )( 5...dxc4 6.e4 { is highly unpleasant. I spent a lot of time making this work, but white has several promising ideas. } )
6. e3{ is met with }
6. dxc4
7. Bxc4
7. a6{ With a much better version of QGA since white has wasted time with  Qc2 . We want to place the  f8 -bishop on  d6 , the  d8 -Queen on  c7 , and play  b5 / b6   Bb7  next. }
