5. Qc2{ The starting point of this chapter is  Qc2 , a very deep and extremely tricky move. }( { The idea is that black cannot play }6...Bb4 { effectively anymore due to }7.a3 Bxc3 8.Qxc3! { where black has given up the bishop pair without spoiling white's pawn structure on the queenside. After spending numerous hours and rewriting a full chapter because I wasn't satisfied with the previous suggestion, I recommend challenging white's center immediately. } )
5. c5{ Exploiting the fact that the  d4  pawn is slightly vulnerable after the Queen moves to  c2 . What I like most about this move that it is the most direct & strategically principled move. The alternatives have their own problems. }( 5...c6 6.e3 { transposes to Meran, which is outside the scope of this course. } )( 5...dxc4 6.e4 { is highly unpleasant. I spent a lot of time making this work, but white has several promising ideas. } )
6. cxd5( { The only challenging attempt, white forces an isolated pawn. }6.dxc5 Nxc5 7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Nxd5 exd5 {  transposes.  } )
6. Nxd5( { The right exchange. We want to trade the knights since our  d7  knight is misplaced.  6...Nxd5  introduces the option of playing  ...Nf6  sometime later in the game. }6...exd5 { is worse due to }7.g3 { where we have a misplaced knight on  d7 . } )
7. Nxd5
7. exd5{ Although we have a damaged pawn structure, our pieces have access to good squares. The bishop is coming to  d6  next, and the  d7 -knight is going to jump  f6 / c5  (after  cxd4 ) followed by ... Ne4 . To compensate for the structural defect, we need to be quick and exploit the potential activity of our pieces. }
8. g3{ The most played move in the position. White wants to get the structure as Dubov wanted with early  g3 , but without allowing the option of  Nb4 . The drawback is this move allows }
8. c4{ With the same idea of gaining space and avoiding doubled-pawns. We want to play  Nf6 , after exchanging our dark-squared Bishops with  Bb4 . }
9. Bg2
9. Bb4+{ Developing the Bishop with check. White is forced to play }
10. Bd2
10. Bxd2+{ Forced. }
11. Nxd2{ Looking to attack  d5 . }
11. Nf6{ our plan. the  c8 -bishop can be developed to  g4  now. }
12. O-O
12. O-O
13. b3{ The only try. White has to undermine the  c4  pawn.  b5  isn't possible due to the pin by the  g2 -Bishop. }
13. cxb3{ forced. }
14. Nxb3{ White wants to play  Nc5  next, but after }
14. b6{ followed by  Ba6 - Re8 - Rc8 , attacking white's weaknesesses. Black is pushing a bit. }
