11. Bxc5{ This natural move is somehow not the main move. Black players preferred  Ba6  here, after Magnus defeated Ding in a spectacular fashion. This move came into the limelight after Arjun defeated Max Warmerdam in a miniature game at the Tata Steel Challengers.     Black simply recaptures the pawn and asks white to exploit our loose pieces. It's important to note that even though both  d5  knight and  c5  bishop are exposed to tactics, they are very actively placed in the centre. We place our bets on white not being able to exploit the loose position of our pieces, after which we'll take over the initiative due to better positioning of our pieces. Our typical idea is to bring the Bishop to  a6 ,  b8 -knight to  d7 / c6 , and one of the rooks to  c8 . }
12. e4{ The main move and the one which poses most concrete questions. White forces us to move back with the knight. However, the move has a significant drawback.  e4  shuts down the activity of  g2 -bishop. }
12. Nb6{ Keeping the knight on the queenside makes more sense strategically. We are looking to exploit white's lack of development/weaknesses on the queenside. }
13. Ncd2{ The second most popular move. This was played by GM Maghsoodloo and GM Warmerdam. }( { Just like }13.Ne3 { , white attacks our bishop on  c5 . However, the difference is that after }13...Na6 { , white has the additional option of  14.Nb3 , reinforcing the attack on  c5 -bishop. } )
13. N8d7{ Forced. If white is slow, we'll take over the initiative with ... Ba6 / Rc8 . }( 13...Na6?! 14.Nb3± { followed by  Rd1  &  Bf1 / Nc5  ideas. We are under serious pressure here. } )
14. a5{ The most consistent. White traps the knight on  b6 . }
14. Ba6{ There's no time to waste! As I previously explained, we need to constantly improve our pieces, even at the cost of other strategic factors. With ... Ba6 , we're prepared to exchange two minor pieces for a rook and a pawn. Typically, such trades favor the side with the minor pieces, as they offer more flexibility. However, we pin our hopes on our activity, asserting that this activity should compensate for the material deficit. }
15. axb6{ White needs to be equally quick too. The side that blinks first will be reduced to ashes here. }
15. Rc8{ This is an important intermezzo. We move our rook to a better square with tempo. There are five games in practical play at this point, all against 2500+ opposition! }
16. Qd1{ This is the direction all games in this variation take, with the exception of the Max-Arjun game. White keeps the queen near the kingside, which is the new center of attention. }
16. Qxb6{ We're improving the queen with a useful recapture. The threat of ... Bxf1  remains alive since  Re1  is not possible due to ... Bxf2 +. Even though we are a whole piece down for a pawn, the difference in quality of pieces keeps us in the game with equal chances. We'll be creating opportunities on both flanks, the queenside and kingside. }
17. Rxa6{ This is another possible way to deal with the pressure. White decides to surrender the  a1 -rook instead of the  f1 , thus alleviating the pressure on  f2  since our queen is compelled to move to  a6 . The drawback for white is that our queen will now exert pressure on the queenside from the a-file as well. }
17. Qxa6{ Our queen is ready to penetrate on the a-file. }
18. Nb3{ Bringing the knight to where it belongs, the queenside. The knight wasn't going to contribute anything on  f3 . }
18. Qa2{ The best form of defense is counterattack. We don't want to let white develop easily. Our pieces are breathing down white's neck. }
19. Nxc5{ This helps us improve our pieces now. }
19. Nxc5{ This will result in us winning some material. }
