5. Bg2{ White continues with their plan of placing the bishop on the  h1 - a8  diagonal. }
5. O-O{ We finish our kingside development. }
6. O-O{ This is the main line. White finishes their kingside development too. }
6. dxc4( { The main move in this position along with }6...c6 { . We go for the counter attacking strategy of attacking white's central pawns. } )
7. Qc2{ The main move by far. White looks to recapture on  c4 , keeping a small advantage due to more space. }
7. b5{ The first deviation from the main lines. We play ambitiously and not let white take up the  c4  pawn so easily. }( 7...a6 { is the main line. It's very solid, but doesn't give too many winning chances to black. White keeps a tiny space advantage. } )
8. a4{ Challenging the pawns on  b5  &  c4 . }
8. b4{ The most ambitious. We gain space and stop  Nc3  ideas. }
9. Nfd2{ Principled. White activates the  g2 -bishop and look to capture the pawn on  c4  with the knight. }
9. Nd5{ We stop  Bxa8  and improve the position of our knight. }
10. Nxc4{ The point of  Nfd2 . White gets the knight on the outpost. }
10. c5{ Looking to undermine white's centre. }
11. dxc5{ The main move. White accepts the challenge and wants to play against the  d5 -knight. }
11. Bxc5{ This natural move is somehow not the main move. Black players preferred  Ba6  here, after Magnus defeated Ding in a spectacular fashion. This move came into the limelight after Arjun defeated Max Warmerdam in a miniature game at the Tata Steel Challengers.     Black simply recaptures the pawn and asks white to exploit our loose pieces. It's important to note that even though both  d5  knight and  c5  bishop are exposed to tactics, they are very actively placed in the centre. We place our bets on white not being able to exploit the loose position of our pieces, after which we'll take over the initiative due to better positioning of our pieces. Our typical idea is to bring the Bishop to  a6 ,  b8 -knight to  d7 / c6 , and one of the rooks to  c8 . }
12. e4{ The main move and the one which poses most concrete questions. White forces us to move back with the knight. However, the move has a significant drawback.  e4  shuts down the activity of  g2 -bishop. }
12. Nb6{ Keeping the knight on the queenside makes more sense strategically. We are looking to exploit white's lack of development/weaknesses on the queenside. }
13. Rd1( { The main move. White develops the rook with tempo. }13.Nxb6 axb6 { transposes. } )
13. N8d7{ We continue to develop and bring a new piece into the game. Our idea is to play ... Bb7 / Ba6  next, and bringing the rook into the game. White has a few alternatives here, and we'll examine them one-by-one. }
14. Nxb6{ White tries to ruin our queenside pawn structure. }
14. axb6{ We happily oblige.  axb6  opens up the a-file for our rook as well as strengthens the support of our active, yet vulnerable bishop on  c5 . As discussed many times in this chapter, the primary focus of this variation is to keep the pieces active. We are already in unknown waters. }( 14...Bxb6 { runs into }15.a5! Bxa5 16.Bf4⩲ { preparing  Bd6 . Our Bishop is inactive on  a5  whereas white's pieces are now going to take over. } )
15. e5{ This is another interesting idea. White opens up the diagonal for the  g2 -bishop and gains space. }
15. Ba6{ A fantastic exchange sacrifice. We are happy to trade the light-squared bishop, the only defender of the white king, with our inactive rook on  a8 . }
16. Bxa8{ Forced for all practical purposes. Black was threatening ... Rc8 . }
16. Qxa8{ With a huge attack on the kingside. Our threat is to play  Qf3 - Bb7 , with the battery being decisive. }
17. Rxd7{ The only way to keep the balance. }
17. Qf3{ With the threat of  Be2 . White's defence is not easy at all. }
18. Qd2( { With the threat of meeting }18...Be2 { with }19.Qe1 { . } )
18. Rc8( { We reignite the threat of }19.-- ...Bxf2 { since }20.Qxf2 { is met with }21...Rxc1 { , followed by a mate. } )
19. Nc3{ This is not pleasant for white at all. }
19. bxc3
20. bxc3
20. h5{ We keep a huge attack while being just an exchange down. Our threat is to play ... h4 - h3  next, or to play ... Bc4 - d5 . }
