9. Nbd2{ The most popular sideline. White develops a piece and looks to recapture on  c4  with the knight. The downside of this move is black is allowed to play a strong reply now. }
9. Bb7{ With the idea of challenging white's  g2 -bishop on the diagonal. Our bishop is ideally placed on  b7 , keeping an eye on the important  e4  &  d5  squares. }
10. Nxc4{ White wins back the pawn and keeps a small strategic edge due to the extra space, thanks to the  d4  pawn. }
10. c5{ An important strategic move. We challenge white's central superiority and look to undermine the important  d4 -pawn. }
11. Rd1{ Was another possible way to play, tried by GM Yu Yangyi and GM Georg Meier among others. White doesn't concede the d-file immedately and keeps the central tension. }
11. Nbd7
12. Bf4{ The point behind white's plan. White provoked  Nbd7  so that the  d6  square is no longer defended by the Queen. White is preparing  Nd6 . That being said, this is not too critical of a try. Black is alright in many ways, the simplest being }
12. Bd5{ Centralising the bishop and getting out of the attack on  b7  after  Nd6 . We are preparing  Rc8  again and thus, white needs to make a decision with the knights. }
13. Nfe5{ The most direct. White threatens  Bxd5  or  Nc6 , looking to exploit the weak-square on  c6 . We can react comfortably. }( 13.dxc5 Be4 { and the white queen is awkwardly stuck. }14.Qb3 { runs into }14...Nxc5 { and }14.Qd2 { runs into }14...Nxc5⩱ { as well. } )
13. Rc8{ Bringing the inactive rook into the game. We are threatning  cxd4 , so white needs to be quick. }
14. e4{ The only real challenging try. White gains space in the centre and forces us to take some correct decisions. }
14. Bxc4( { Forced. We couldn't afford to lose time with }14...Bb7 { . } )
15. Qxc4{ This is a very logical move too. White recaptures the piece and threatens  dxc5 . }
15. Nxe5( { The simplest. }15...cxd4 { was quite alright too, but this is easier to remember. } )
16. Bxe5{ The most logical. White doesn't want to create a doubled pawn unnecessarily. }( 16.dxe5 Nd7 { was quite comfortable for Black. We could look to get out of the pin and play  g5  next, attacking the weak pawn on  e5 . } )
16. cxd4{ We open up the c-file for our rook. }
17. Qxd4
17. Qa5{ With the threat of ... Rfd8 . Black is slightly better. }
