( { Chapter 13 deals with White's alternatives on move 8 & 9 after   }6...dxc4 7.Qc2 b5 { . Most of them are harmless, but }9.Ne5 { seems to be the most challenging. Without wasting much time, let's get started! } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. Be7( 5.Nc3 { is white's main alternative in this position. However, after }5...Nbd7 { we transpose to  chapter 10.  } )
5. Bg2
5. O-O
6. O-O
6. dxc4
7. Qc2
7. b5
8. a4
8. b4( { In the previous chapter, we looked at }9.Nfd2 { in this position. We would be covering all of white's alternatives here, }9.Nbd2 { , }9.Ne5 9.Qxc4 { and }9.Bg5 { . } )( 8...c6 9.axb5 cxb5 10.Ng5 Nd5 { is not possible due to }11.Qxh7#!  )
9. Ne5{ The most challenging sideline in my opinion. White wins an exchange for a knight and 2 pawns. However, our pawns on  c4  &  c7  are slightly weak. }
9. Qxd4{ Accepting the challenge. }
10. Bxa8{ Forced. Other moves run into ... Nd5 , where black remains a pawn up. }
10. Qxe5{ With a complex strategic position on board. White has an extra exchange for a knight and 2 pawns, but has a weaker kingside and undeveloped pieces. It's important to note that black has ... Qh5 - Ng4  ideas in the air. Black on the other hand, has couple of weak pawns on  c4  &  c7 . Furthermore, our knight on  c8  and the bishop on  a8  are out of the game temporarily. }
11. Bf3{ Retreating with the Bishop is weaker as black can keep the dangerous pawns on  c4  &  b4  alive with }
11. Ba6{ with the threat of  b3  at some point. Minor piece + 2 pawns usually overpower the exchange in middlegames with heavy pieces, with this position being no exception. Black has more than sufficient compensation here. }
12. Bf4{ White develops a piece with tempo. }( 12.Nd2 b3-+ { is already resignable for white. Black's pawns are dominating the board. } )
12. Qa5{ we keep the  c7 -pawn guarded and prepare  b3 . }
13. Nd2{ bringing the last piece in }
13. b3{ The crucial intermezzo. Black is already better here. }
14. Qc1( 14.Nxc4 { loses material after }14...Qb4∓ { with a double attack on  c4  &  c2 . } )
14. Qb4{ We guard the active pawn on  c4  and are ready to give up the  c7 -pawn for activity. If white takes up the challenge with }
15. Bxc7{ we can simply play }
15. Nd5{ Preparing ... Bf6 / Nd5 / Nd4 . The activity of our pieces is far more important than the pawn on  c7 . White's pieces are literally getting suffocated here. }
16. Bxd5{ Also doesn't help white's case. }
16. exd5{ Our pawn on  c4  only gets strengthened. We are already winning here. }
