( { Chapter 14 deals with   }7.Ne5 { , one of the biggest challenges if you want to play for a win as black against the Catalan. Usually, white gets a comfortable two-result position where we need to suffer a bit. I think I came up with an extremely rare & an interesting idea that prolongs the fight and gives us the chances we want. } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. Be7( 5.Nc3 { is white's main alternative in this position. However, after }5...Nbd7 { we transpose to  chapter 10.  } )
5. Bg2
5. O-O
6. O-O
6. dxc4
7. Ne5{ The starting point of the chapter. White wants to recapture with the knight, and not let us  play ... b7 - b5 , unlike the  Qc2  variations. }( { The main line goes with }7....Nc6 { , after which white has couple of decent tries with }8.Nxc6 { & }8.Bxc6 { , where white keeps a comfortable position with chances to push. } )
7. Nd5{ Here comes our surprise. Our idea is simple: we want to keep pieces on the board and fight for a win. With 7... Nd5 , we are threatening to play ... b5  next, supporting the  c4 -pawn.     Out of the 5500-odd games played here, only 59 continued with ... Nd5 . More importantly, it's been played just 4 times in GM practice, which gives us an indication of how big of a surprise this is. }
8. a4{ Is also a logical way to stop  b5 . However, we have the counterattacking }
8. c5{ here which undermines white's centre. This wasn't available in the  Qc2  lines since our Bishop would have been under attack after  dxc5   Bxc5   Qxc4 . }
9. e4{ The only challenging attempt. White gains space in the centre and challenging our knight. }( 9.dxc5 Bxc5 { helps us improves the position of our bishop. } )
9. Nb4{ Improving our knight, and bringing it to the outpost. From  b4 , the knight keeps an eye on the weak  d3 -square too. }
10. d5{ White's point. White gets a passed pawn in the centre. However, the activity of our pieces fully neutralises the effect of the passed pawn. }
10. Nd7{ Developing the worst-placed piece and prompting white to trade off the active knight for our passive one. }
11. Nxc4{ Of course, white will grab the pawn back. }
11. Nb6{ Our point. We attack the  d5 -pawn and force white to either trade the active knight, or play  Ne3  and shut down the  c1 -bishop. }
12. Ne3{ White defends the  d5 -pawn and threatens  a5 . }
12. a5{ The last important move. We have stopped white's threat and are ready to improve our position with ... Bf6 - Bd4 . }
13. Nc3{ White develops their piece. }
13. Bf6{ The position on the board is sharp. We have some incredible pieces, yet white does possess a passed pawn, albeit it's weak. Depending on white's concrete response, we might continue with ... Bd7  or opt to play ... Bd4 / exd5 . A typical strategy could involve blockading the d-pawn with the knight. An example of this might be to execute ... Bd7 , followed by ... exd5 - Nc8 - Nd6 . This lively position provides ample opportunities for the superior player to emerge victorious. }
