8. b5{ Our point. We gain space on the queenside and make way for our bishop, preparing ... Bb7 . Unlike the traditional main line with  7...Nc6 , we do get fighting chances here. }
9. Na5{ This is the top choice of the engines. It may appear strange, but white stops ... Bb7 , and prepares for  Nc3  next, to be followed by  Nb3  at some point. }
9. c5{ The most logical response which seemingly refutes white's concept of  Na5 . However, white has a spectacular move now. }
10. Nc3( { With the point that }10...Qxa5 { runs into }11.Nxd5 exd5 12.Bxd5 { , winning material! } )
10. a6{ We defend our  b5 -pawn and prepare ... Qxa5  next. Our rook can now escape via  a7 . }
11. Nxd5{ Logical response. White creates an isolated pawn on  d5 . }
11. exd5{ We are again renewing the threat of ... Qxa5 , and meeting  Nb3  with ... c4 . White has an extraordinary move. }
12. Bf4( { This is the crux of the operation that starts with  Na5 . The issue is that }12...Qxa5 { would run into }13.Bxd5 { , and we can't play }13...Ra7 { due to }{ . Nevertheless, we do have an appropriate response. } )
12. c4{ We're gaining space on the queenside and, importantly, preventing  dxc5 . We're still not threatening ... Qxa5 , but are prepared for ... Be6  next, after which ... Qa5  becomes a significant threat.     After  c4 , white's knight on  a5  lacks favorable squares. White has a couple of crucial attempts to consider. }( 12...Qxa5 { runs into }13.Bxd5 Ra7 14.Bxb8±  )
13. Qd2{ The most logical response. The Queen defends the knight from  d2 , connecting the rooks. White is ready to open up the position with  e4  next, since it's preferable for them due to better pieces and space. The downside of  Qd2  is that the  f4  Bishop faces some concrete problems. }
13. Be6{ We develop our minor piece and are ready to meet  e4 . }
14. b3{ The most testing try. White pokes our Queenside pawns. We need to be resourceful here. }( 14.e4 { is met with }14...dxe4 15.Bxe4 Bd5! { where white is left with an isolated pawn on  d4 . We'll follow up with  Bf6  next. White has no real targets here. } )( 14.Rfe1 { is met by the simple & logical }14...Qd7 { with the idea of developing our last minor piece with  Nc6 . Once we do that, we'll end up with a more mobile pawn structure on the queenside. } )
14. g5{ A very unexpected but an extremely strong response. We want to dislodge the Bishop from  f4  and push it back to  e3 . }
15. Be3{ The most logical. It seems that white is much better and is ready to play  bxc4  next. }
15. c3{ The point. After }
16. Qxc3
16. b4{ winning a piece with  Qxa5  coming on the next move. This doesn't work with the Bishop on  f4  since white would have  Qc7 ! }
