( { Chapter 14 deals with   }7.Ne5 { , one of the biggest challenges if you want to play for a win as black against the Catalan. Usually, white gets a comfortable two-result position where we need to suffer a bit. I think I came up with an extremely rare & an interesting idea that prolongs the fight and gives us the chances we want. } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. Be7( 5.Nc3 { is white's main alternative in this position. However, after }5...Nbd7 { we transpose to  chapter 10.  } )
5. Bg2
5. O-O
6. O-O
6. dxc4
7. Ne5{ The starting point of the chapter. White wants to recapture with the knight, and not let us  play ... b7 - b5 , unlike the  Qc2  variations. }( { The main line goes with }7....Nc6 { , after which white has couple of decent tries with }8.Nxc6 { & }8.Bxc6 { , where white keeps a comfortable position with chances to push. } )
7. Nd5{ Here comes our surprise. Our idea is simple: we want to keep pieces on the board and fight for a win. With 7... Nd5 , we are threatening to play ... b5  next, supporting the  c4 -pawn.     Out of the 5500-odd games played here, only 59 continued with ... Nd5 . More importantly, it's been played just 4 times in GM practice, which gives us an indication of how big of a surprise this is. }
8. Nxc4{ Winning the pawn back. }
8. b5{ Our point. We gain space on the queenside and make way for our bishop, preparing ... Bb7 . Unlike the traditional main line with  7...Nc6 , we do get fighting chances here. }
9. Ncd2{ This is another logical attempt. White wants to play  Nb3  next, putting pressure on the weak square on  c5 . }
9. a5{ With the intention of playing ... a4  next. Our typical plan is to get ... c5  in, which can only be achieved if the knight is not stable on  b3 . }
10. Nc3{ The only real way to stop  c5  ideas. White threatens the typical  Nxd5 / Nb5 . }
10. c6( { Forced. We want to meet }11.Nxd5 { with }11...cxd5 { , eliminating our backward pawn. We have space on the queenside so if we get  ...Nd7 - N7b6 / f6  in, we'll be better. } )
11. a4{ Trying to poke holes on our Queenside. }
11. b4{ forced. We don't want to spoil our pawn structure on the Queenside. }
12. Nce4{ The only way to stop  c5  and not improve our pawn structure with  cxd5 . With  Ne4 , white threatens to play  Nb3  next, keeping a grip over the  c5  square. We can't let this happen, so we play }
12. Nd7{ With the idea of meeting }
13. Nb3
13. f5{ Forcing the knight back. White doesn't want to trade on  c5 , as the c-file we'll be closed after all the trades and  c6  will no longer be a weakness. Furthermore, the pawn on  f5  attacks the  e4  square, so dislodging our knight from  d5  we'll no longer be an option. }
14. Ned2{ White is ready to play  e4  next, opening up the centre so we must deal confidently with }
14. c5{ The entire point of our play. Once we get  c5  in, our position is quite comfortable. We'll play  Qb6 - Bb7  next, followed by getting the  d7  knight and the rooks to better squares. }
