5. O-O
6. O-O
6. dxc4
7. Qa4{ With the intention of recapturing on  c4  without letting us to play  b5 . A clever idea against our repertoire, but we are ready to unleash one of the biggest surprises in the Catalan :) }
7. Qd5{ Among the 1900 odd games available, this move has been employed in 28 games. In the Live Chess Database on ChessBase, it ranks as the 6th most frequently played move. To top it off, the computer initially assigns a "+="  :)  advantage to White. This makes it quite challenging for our opponent to prepare against it.    However, the move is extremely logical. With ... Qd5 , we capitalize on the fact that white's queen on  a4  is misplaced. We defend the  c4 -pawn and are ready to play ... b5  next, reinforcing the defense of the  c4 -pawn. Although this move has been employed in a handful of GM games, it has not garnered the attention it deserves. Unlike the main line with  a6 , the position here is quite dynamic, and white has ample opportunities to make mistakes. }
8. Bg5{ This was tried against GM Kovalenko Igor. White's idea is to capture on  f6  next, followed by  Nc3   Qc6   Qc2 , threatening  Ng5  &  Qh7 #. Very ambitious, but we can easily counter this. }
8. h6{ We force the matters. We don't want the bishop lurking over. }
9. Bxf6
9. Bxf6{ We have won the bishop pair too. There's only one testing reply for white now. }
10. Nc3{ Attacking our queen and forcing the next reply. }
10. Qc6{ Our typical response against  Nc3 . We keep the  c4 -pawn guarded and keep an eye over the  a4 -queen. }
11. Qc2{ With the dual threat of  Ng5  &  Ne4 . }
11. Qa6{ This is the best square for our queen, when faced with white's discovery ideas. From  a6 , we keep the  c4 -pawn guarded and vacate the  c6 -square for our knight. }
12. Ne4{ The most logical follow-up. White opens up the c-file, looking to increasing the pressure over  c4  and attack  f6  at the same time. }
12. Be7{ Forced. We had to get the bishop out of the attack. We are following Adly-Aronian from a different move order now. Our plan is to play ... Nc6  next, if white allows it. }
13. Rfc1{ A very interesting attempt by Adly. White brings the rook into the game, attacking  c4  and stopping ... Nc6  at the same time. }( { If we play }13...Nc6 { here, White can play }14.Qxc4 Qxc4 15.Rxc4 { , with our knight on  c6  being skewered due to the hanging pawn on  c7 . } )
13. Nc6{ (informational) runs into }
14. Qxc4
14. Qxc4
15. Rxc4
