11. Qa6{ This is the best square for our queen, when faced with white's discovery ideas. From  a6 , we keep the  c4 -pawn guarded and vacate the  c6 -square for our knight. }
12. Ne4{ The most logical follow-up. White opens up the c-file, looking to increasing the pressure over  c4  and attack  f6  at the same time. }
12. Be7{ Forced. We had to get the bishop out of the attack. We are following Adly-Aronian from a different move order now. Our plan is to play ... Nc6  next, if white allows it. }
13. Rfc1{ A very interesting attempt by Adly. White brings the rook into the game, attacking  c4  and stopping ... Nc6  at the same time. }( { If we play }13...Nc6 { here, White can play }14.Qxc4 Qxc4 15.Rxc4 { , with our knight on  c6  being skewered due to the hanging pawn on  c7 . } )
13. Nd7{ We develop the knight from the other square here. Aronian played the natural ... Rd8 , which was a slight inaccuracy. With ... Nd7 , Our idea is to play ... b6 - Bb7  next so white needs to force matters. }
14. Qxc4{ Grabing the pawn back. }
14. Qxc4{ We are happy to trade the active queen for our passive one. }
15. Rxc4
15. c6{ We're defending the  c7 -pawn. On the board, we have a highly complex strategic position. White has more space and somewhat active pieces, but we retain the advantage of a pair of bishops. If we can break open the center or move our pieces to optimal squares, we would be in a better position from a strategic perspective.     We aim to play ... a5 - a4 - Ra5  at some point, improving our rook and threatening ... e5 , after which we'll be able to move our  d7 -knight and bring our  c8 -bishop into the game.     This is exactly the type of position where the better player can aim to play for a long game, preserving some chances of winning. Have fun! }
