7. Qa4{ With the intention of recapturing on  c4  without letting us to play  b5 . A clever idea against our repertoire, but we are ready to unleash one of the biggest surprises in the Catalan :) }
7. Qd5{ Among the 1900 odd games available, this move has been employed in 28 games. In the Live Chess Database on ChessBase, it ranks as the 6th most frequently played move. To top it off, the computer initially assigns a "+="  :)  advantage to White. This makes it quite challenging for our opponent to prepare against it.    However, the move is extremely logical. With ... Qd5 , we capitalize on the fact that white's queen on  a4  is misplaced. We defend the  c4 -pawn and are ready to play ... b5  next, reinforcing the defense of the  c4 -pawn. Although this move has been employed in a handful of GM games, it has not garnered the attention it deserves. Unlike the main line with  a6 , the position here is quite dynamic, and white has ample opportunities to make mistakes. }
8. Bf4{ Was tried in the earliest GM game in this variation, against GM Andrey Sumets. White exerts pressure on our  c7  pawn. }
8. b5{ GM Sumets tried  Bd6 , but the simple and most logical move seems to be the strongest. }
9. Qc2{ White wants to give a discovery with the knight next, so we play the unorthodox }
9. Qb7{ This is probably what Sumets missed. We can meet  Ng5 / Ne5  ideas with  c6 / Nd5  and keep our pawn on  c4 . White has some compensation, but we keep a healthy complicated position on the board. If it's possible, we want to play  Nd5 - Nc6  next. }
