[Result "*"]

( { In chapter 16, we'll deal with all of white's alternatives on moves 5 and 6 in the Catalan. White has plenty of options, but   }6.Qc2 { stands out as a very serious alternative, which has been tried by several top players. } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. Be7( 5.Nc3 { is white's main alternative in this position. However, after }5...Nbd7 { we transpose to  chapter 10.  } )
5. Bg2
5. O-O
6. Qc2{ The most challenging 6th move alternative for white. White stops us from playing  dxc4 , as they would recapture on  c4  immediately without allowing us the option to play  b5 . The drawback however, is that white's king is still in the centre and the  d4 -pawn is slightly vulnerable. We try to exploit this. }( 6.Nc3 Nbd7 { transposes to  chapter 10.  } )( 6.Qb3 { transposes. } )
6. c5{ We attempt to open up the center for a couple of reasons. Firstly, we aim to eliminate white's space advantage in the center. Secondly, since white's king is in the center and we have already castled, opening up the center is beneficial for us. }
7. O-O{ This is also a recognized move. By finishing the development, White prepares to initiate action in the center. }
7. cxd4{ We don't allow white that opportunity and start the action ourselves. }
8. Nxd4
8. e5{ While not the most popular, it's certainly the most ambitious move strategically. We gain space in the center, pushing the knight away from the center in the process. }
9. Nf5{ Threatning to capture on  e7 . }
9. d4{ We don't mind that, and continue with our plan of increasing space. White has a couple of ways to continue. }
10. Nxe7+{ White wins the bishop, claiming the bishop pair. }( 10.Bg5 { is quite similar to the main line and transposes after }10...Nc6 11.Nd2 h6 12.Nxe7+ Qxe7 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.c5 { . } )
10. Qxe7{ We recapture the bishop, looking to complete our development with ... Nc6  next, and gain space with ... e4  if possible. At this point, white has two possible approaches. }
11. b4{ This is quite interesting. White has double bishops and is trying to gain space on the queenside to counterbalance our space advantage. }
11. Rd8( 11...Qxb4 { ran into }{ . With }11...Rd8 { , we get out of the pin, improve our rook and threaten  ...Qxb4 . } )
12. c5{ Gives up the control over the  d5 -square. We can continue developing naturally. }
12. Nc6( { With a better position for us. }13.a3 { runs into }13...a5 { , and }14.b5 { is met with  ... d3 - Nd4   ideas, followed by capturing back one of the pawns. We remain better due to activity and space. } )
