{ Chapter 17 addresses White's strategy to play a 'delayed Catalan', postponing  c2 - c4  as long as possible. This can be a complex maneuver, but after dedicating an entire chapter to the Reversed London setup against the Delayed Catalan, I realized that we could simply play 2... e6  and transpose to our Catalan lines, thus bypassing all the complications. }1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. g3{ The most common way of reaching the Delayed Catalan setup. White wants to play  Bg2 - O-O , and play  c4  at the right time. }
3. e6{ The double exclamation mark is not so much to indicate the merit of the move, but rather to console myself. Initially, my recommendation was to opt for the Reversed London setup with  Bf5 , which is objectively the strongest move. Since this chapter was prepared before I finalized my recommendation for the Catalan, it made sense to examine this. However, after writing the entire chapter on  Bf5 , I had a moment of realization: 'Hey, isn't transposing after  e6  much better?' Consequently, three hours of work were wasted. Thus, if I am rewriting the chapter, I might as well reward it with a '!!' to make it more bearable for me. }( { Returning to chess, I still believe that }3...Bf5 { is the strongest move objectively. From a strategic perspective, we move the bishop out before shutting down the  c8 - h3  diagonal. However, we can save a lot of memorization effort if we transpose with  e6 . } )
4. Bg2{ White doesn't have too many tries that can only look to deviate after move 5. }
4. Be7{ We continue developing in Catalan fashion, hoping to transpose after  c4 . }
5. O-O
5. O-O{ This is the moment where white can deviate a bit. }
6. b3{ Possibly the only sensible deviation. White wants to play  Bb2 - c4  next, without allowing us to reach the catalan positions with ... dxc4 . }
6. c5{ We break the centre in the typical fashion. }
7. e3{ was played by GM Puranik. Black couldn't capitalise in the game, but after }
7. b5{ Black is better due to  c4  coming in next, gaining space. }
