1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. Qc2{ This has been tried by a few top GM's, namely Riazantsev and Artemiev. White's idea is to take back on  c4  with the queen, keeping space and preventing the  c5  break. Nevertheless, moving the queen so early in the game has its own drawbacks. }
4. dxc4{ We are happy to trade white would need to spend time on another move with the Queen. }
5. Qxc4
5. a6{ preparing to win a tempo with  b5 , followed by  Bb7 . }
6. Bf4{ White's main response. The idea is stop  b5  as the  c7  pawn is under attack. }
6. Bd6{ reinforcing the threat of  b5 . }
7. Bxd6{ White's safest bet. }
7. cxd6{ This is the correct recapture. There's a well-known guideline relevant here, stating that you should capture towards the center during the opening and middlegame. By choosing ... cxd6 , our pawn controls the critical  e5  square and opens up the c-file for our rook. Our strategy is to play ... b5 - Bb7 - O-O - Nbd7 / Nc6 - Rc8  next, in some order. }
