3. Nf6
4. h3{ Not part of the course initially, but an addition after the infamous Ding-Nepo game. White's setup is aimed against Nepo's QGD, since  Be7  is met by  cxd5   exd5   Nc3   c6   Bf4   Bf5   g4 !?, with a fresh position on the board, revealed in the alleged leaked games of Ding. It's an excellent one-game try against QGD players, but not even a decent one against our setup. }
4. Nbd7{ We are consistent with our setup. With  Nbd7 , we renew the threat of  dxc4  and  Nb6 . We are already in our comfort zone, winning an extra tempo over the regular lines. There were a couple of online games allegedly between Ding & Rapport, so we continue a bit further. }
5. Nc3{ runs into }
5. dxc4{ followed by  e3 - Nb6 , or  e4 - b5 , versions of which we have already studied. }
