5. Nbd2{ White wants to stay independent and not transpose to the Manhattan with  Nc3 . However, the knight on  d2  is clearly misplaced. }
5. dxc4{ Exploiting the fact that we have  b5  ideas in the air since the white's knight is on  d2 . }
6. e3
6. b5{ The most ambitious move strategically. We keep the extra pawn and ask white to show their compensation. White's best bet it to force us to liquidate. }
7. Be2( { This move was also attempted by Shakh. It's better than }7.a4 { , but still quite harmless. We can now continue with natural development. } )
7. Bb7{ Preparing ... O-O  & ... c5 . }
8. O-O{ White gets out the pin and safeguards the king. }
8. O-O{ So do we. We are ready to play ... c5  next. }
9. b3{ White's idea. White wants to open up the queenside before we do it with ... c5 . }
9. c3{ Sticking true to our plan. We don't want to face a passive position after  cxb3   Nxb3 , where white is the one posing problems. Instead, we keep our pieces active, even if we have to give our pawn back. }
10. Nb1{ Forced. }
10. c5{ We stick true to our strategy and challenge white's centre. White needs to be accurate now. }
11. Bxb5{ This allows us to take over. }
11. Qa5
12. Be2
12. Rd8{ Where we are dominating the queenside and the centre. }
