3. Nf6
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. Bg5
5. Bb4
6. e3
6. h6
7. Bh4
7. g5
8. Bg3
8. Ne4
9. a3{ Is a very clever try. White tempts us to win the pawn on  c3 , which is inaccurate due to tactical reasons. }
9. Bxc3+{ We give the Bishop, since  Nxc3  was inferior. With  Bxc3 , we spoil white's pawn structure on the queenside. }( 9...Nxc3 { runs into }10.Qb3 { it seems we win a pawn after }10...Bxa3 { but }11.bxc3 Be7 12.Nf3 { is better for white. Look at the difference in the activity of the pieces! } )
10. bxc3{ White wins the Bishop pair, and wants to finish development with  Bd3 - Ne2  next. }( 10...Nxc3 { runs into }11.Qc2 Ne4 12.Bxc7± { White remains better due to the pair of bishops. } )
10. Nc6{ Preparing ... Nxc3 , by blocking the c-file. We develop a piece and control the  e5  square, which reintroduces the threat of  h5 - h4 . }
11. Bd3{ White continues with the plan of finishing the development. }
11. Bf5{ A very clever idea by us. We develop our Bishop, preparing  Qe7 - O-O-O , as well as renewing the threat of  Nxc3 . We deliberately place the Bishop on  f5 , so that it can be exchanged after  Nxg3 , which would weaken the  c4 -square. The light-squared Bishop is the worst piece in QGD structures, so exchanging them is a good idea in general. }( 11...Nxc3 { winning a pawn still doesn't work due to }12.Qb3 Ne4 13.Bxe4 dxe4 14.h4± { . } )
12. Ne2{ White finishes development, and defends  c3 . }
12. Qe7{ Same stuff. We prepare ... O-O-O . We keep the queen on  e7  and not on  d7 , since it can attack  e3  after  f3   Nxg3 . Black won a model game in  David-Sethuraman 0-1.  }
