13. Qd6{ We refine our setup. We are ready to play  Bd7  next, followed by 0-0-0. We don't mind giving up the pawn and bank our hopes on the activity of our pieces. }
14. Nh3{ White remains consistent with the plan }
14. Bd7{ our point.  Nxg5  runs into  Qe7 , followed by  Qxe3 . We want to play  f6 , but that is met with  Qg6 + }
15. O-O{ White safeguards the king and is ready to open up the centre next. }
15. O-O-O{ We remain consistent with our strategy of prioritizing activity over material. With 0-0-0, we finish our development, even at the cost of a pawn. Something like  Rg8  would have given White time to start making threats. We are ready to play  f6 / f5  next, followed by assault against the  e3  pawn. }
16. Nxg5{ Forced, as white cannot allow us to play  f6  and consolidate. }
16. Rdf8{ The real point. We want to play  f5  next, and open up the kingside. }
17. Nh3{ White retreats, planning to meet }
17. f5{ with }
18. g5{ and if white is allowed to play  f4  next, white is practically winning due to the protected passed pawn. }
18. f4{ Strong & consistent. We are ready to give up some material, so keep our initiative going. }
19. Nxf4{ White is a couple of pawns up, yet we keep going with }
19. Rxf4
20. exf4
20. Qxf4{ We are an exchange and a pawn down. However, in return, we have several elements in our favor. The dark squares, namely the  g5  and  d4  squares, as well as the  e3  square are weak. We possess the dark-squared bishop while white doesn't. We have threats of  Qxd4 / Nxd4 , as well as opening up the kingside with  h3 , where our rook is conveniently placed. The position is objectively equal, with both sides having chances. }
