( { Chapter 23 deals with white's sidelines on move 8 after   }6...h6 7.Bxf6 { , apart from  8.Qa4+ , which we have covered in the previous chapter. Along with this, we also cover }7.Bf4!? { which has hardly any games, but has been tried by three grandmasters. } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. Bg5
5. Bb4
6. e3
6. h6
7. Bf4{ This is a very new concept, first tried by the German prodigy, GM Vincent Keymer, and then by one of my students, GM Raja Rithvik. White's idea is to meet ... g5  with  Be5 , thereby stopping us from achieving our plans of  Ne4 . The drawback of this move, however, is that White gives up the pin on the  h4 - d8  diagonal. }
7. Bf5{ This natural move is the strongest. We develop our light-squared bishop and are happy to trade it on  d3 , exchanging our worst-placed piece in the QGD structures. }
8. Nf3{ This is timid. }
8. O-O{ We have a very comfortable version of QGD since our light-squared bishop is on  f5 . }
