4. exd5
5. Bg5
5. Bb4
6. e3
6. h6
7. Bxf6
7. Qxf6
8. Qb3{ With  Qb3 , white puts pressure on both  b4 -bishop, and the  d5 -pawn. The drawback though is that white doesn't provoke ... Nc6 . }
8. Qd6{ We keep the  d5 -pawn protected, as well as don't give up the bishop pair so easily. }
9. a3{ The only challenging response. White forces us to give up the bishop. }( 9.Nf3 c6 { is quite similar to  8.Nf3 . } )
9. Bxc3+
10. Qxc3{ White doesn't want to spoil the queenside pawn structure with  bxc3 . }
10. Bf5{ Standard by now. We are happy to trade the bishops on  d3  & want to play ... O-O - Nd7 - c6  in some order next. }
11. Qb4( { A small try, to open up the a-file for the a1-rook after }11...Qxb4 12.axb4 { . White stops us from playing  ...Nd7  temporarily. This was tried by the Iranian prodigy GM Daneshvar Bardiya against GM Dominguez. } )
11. Qb6{ We decline the offer to trade queens on  b4  and instead offer to trade on  b6 ! With ... Qb6 , we guard the  b7 -pawn and prepare ... Nd7  next.  Qxb6  is met by ... axb6 , where the a-file is open for our rook. We'll follow up with ... Nd7 - c6  and ... a5 , gaining space on the queenside. }
