( { Chapter 24 deals with White's alternatives on move 5, after   }4.cxd5 exd5 { . There aren't many, but we still need to check a few of them out, especially }5.Bf4 { . } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. Qc2{ This is a possible try too. White stops  Bf5  and wants to play  Bg5  next. The drawback though is that the  d4  pawn is unprotected. }( 5.Nf3 Nbd7 { transposes to the Manhattan. } )
5. c5{ Undermining White's centre. White can continue developing. }
6. Nf3( 6.dxc5 Bxc5 7.Nf3 Nc6 { transposes. } )
6. Nc6{ White can't sustain the pressure in the center any longer.  e3  here shuts down the  c1 -bishop. }
7. dxc5{ But this allows us to bring out our bishop on  f8  in one go. }
7. Bxc5{ With a small edge for us. White usually is happy to trade on  c5 , but since white has wasted some time with  Qc2 , and we haven't spent time on ... Be7 / Bd6 , this continuation has been perfect for us. White is in some trouble already, since  e3  shuts down the bishop. }
8. Bg5
8. Nb4{ Pushing the Queen away from the c-file. }
9. Qd2
9. d4{ White faces some concrete tactical problems due to the ... Nc2  threats. From a strategic viewpoint, we have extra space too. }
