( { Chapter 24 deals with White's alternatives on move 5, after   }4.cxd5 exd5 { . There aren't many, but we still need to check a few of them out, especially }5.Bf4 { . } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. Bf4{ The main alternative, tried mainly by Sarana. Instead of  Bg5 , white brings out the Bishop to the  h2 - b8  diagonal, where it cannot be harassed with  h6 - g5 . Placing the Bishop on  f4  is an upcoming trend in the QGD, so we may need to be careful with this. Black has a lot of ideas, but I like the most forcing move now! }
5. c5{ Putting pressure on  d4  again. This has not been tried by any titled player, (except GM Savchenko in 2014). What I like about the move is that it is quite principled. White's Bishop on  f4  does not attack our  f6 -Knight, which means we can challenge White's center with  c5 . Secondly, it is not played a lot giving us a good chance to catch our opponent off-guard. }
6. dxc5{ Allows us to bring our Bishop into the game. }
6. Bxc5{ White should usually play ... dxc5  once we have committed ... Be7 / Bd6  so that we spend a tempo more on ... Bxc5 . }
7. e3{ What else? White looks to develop the pieces, but so do we. }
7. O-O{ We have finished our kingside development, and look to develop the Queenside pieces next. }
8. Nf3
8. Nc6{ With the threat of  d4 , looking to open up the position since white's King is in the centre. The position is balanced, but we get a fighting position right out of the opening. }
