3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. Bf4{ The main alternative, tried mainly by Sarana. Instead of  Bg5 , white brings out the Bishop to the  h2 - b8  diagonal, where it cannot be harassed with  h6 - g5 . Placing the Bishop on  f4  is an upcoming trend in the QGD, so we may need to be careful with this. Black has a lot of ideas, but I like the most forcing move now! }
5. c5{ Putting pressure on  d4  again. This has not been tried by any titled player, (except GM Savchenko in 2014). What I like about the move is that it is quite principled. White's Bishop on  f4  does not attack our  f6 -Knight, which means we can challenge White's center with  c5 . Secondly, it is not played a lot giving us a good chance to catch our opponent off-guard. }
