{ Chapter 26 addresses White's alternatives on move 4 in the QGD. There aren't many options, but it makes a lot of sense for White to start with  4.Bg5  if they know that we intend to enter the Gukesh QGD. }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bf4{ Isn't much different from 5.Bf4. We continue in a similiar fashion with }
4. c5
5. e3{ The most played move. White wants to recapture on  d4  with the pawn. }
5. cxd4{ We happily accept the offer and ask White to recapture with the e-pawn }
6. exd4
6. dxc4{ We trade the second set of central pawns too and create an isolated pawn on  d4 . This sequence isn't great usually, but White has committed the Bishop early on to  f4 . }
7. Bxc4
7. Bd6{ Exploiting the  f4 -Bishop. We are happy to trade pieces as we have a better pawn structure. If White wastes some time by moving the Bishop, we can play ... h6  or even ... O-O , followed by ... Nc6 - b6 - Bb7  and ... Nb4 / Na5 , a typical plan in IQP positions. }
