1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bg5( { The trickiest 4th move alternative. White doesn't commit to }4.cxd5 { yet, which means our c8-Bishop is closed for the moment. }4...Nbd7 { doesn't make sense for us, since after }5.e3 Bb4 { , we have a worse version of the Manhattan. } )( 4.g3 { transposes to the Catalan after }4...Be7 { . } )
4. dxc4{ We have a twist prepared here, and we won't transpose into the Vienna lines with ... Bb4 . }
5. e4{ This the most ambitious move. White gains space in the centre, and threatens  e5  &  Bxc4 . The drawback of this move is that the  d4 -pawn is slightly vulnerable since it cannot be defended anymore by the e-pawn. }
5. c5{ This was our plan with  dxc4 . We want to undermine White's center with  c5  directly, without going ... Bb4 . }
6. Bxf6{ This is extremely rare, but quite tricky. White eliminates the  f6 -Knight and then pushes  d5 , thereby avoiding all of the ... Nxd5  tricks, as in the main line. However, White gives up the Bishop pair without any real confrontation, giving us ample counterplay. }
6. Qxf6{ Forced, for all practical purposes. }
7. d5{ White gains space, but the drawback is that weakens the dark-squares. }
7. g6{ The drawback of early  Bxf6 ; we are able to develop our Bishop to  g7 . }
8. Bxc4{ White wins the pawn. }( 8.Nf3 { transposes after }8...Bg7 9.e5 Qd8 10.Bxc4 O-O { . } )
8. Bg7{ We bring our Bishop onto the active diagonal. }
9. Nf3{ A normal developing move. }
9. O-O{ We safeguard our king and are ready to start playing on the Queenside/center. Our plan is to play  exd5  next. }
10. e5{ The most ambitious move strategically. White wants to choke us with extra space. However, the  e5  pawn is slightly vulnerable and can be prone to some threats. }
10. Qd8{ We retreat to the initial square.  Qe7  would have allowed White to play  d6  with a tempo. Things are not at all bleak though. We are ready to play  exd5  next and play  Nc6 - Bg4 , where we get our pieces out. Remember that we have a pair of Bishops and the position is pretty open, giving us enough strategic compensation for the lack of development right now. }
11. O-O{ The strongest move objectively. White finishes development, and pokes at our lack of development. }
11. exd5{ We are now looking to change the tides and play  Bg4 / Nc6  next. }
12. Bxd5{ Preventing  Bg4 , is the strongest move objectively. However, we can still play }
12. Nc6{ With a balanced position. We renew the threat of  Bg4 , without being afraid of  Bxc6 , as we'll win a pawn with  Bg4  quickly. }
