5. c5{ Just like in the variation with 5.e4, we look to undermine white's centre with  c5 . }
6. Bxf6{ Just like in the 5.e4 variation, white deflects our Queen and wants to push  d5  next. Out of the 8 odd games OTB, at least 6 of them are in GM practice, with Shakhriyar Mamedyarov being the strongest one to employ this. }
6. Qxf6{ We naturally recapture with the Queen, and threaten  cxd4 . }
7. d5{ White's idea. White gains space, and prepares  Bxc4  next. }
7. a6{ We always look to meet  Bxc4  with  b5 . }
8. a4{ Stopping  b5  also makes sense, and was played by Arjun Erigaisi against Polina Shuvalova. Polina correctly played }
8. Nd7{ With the intention of meeting }
9. Bxc4
9. Nb6{ After which we win the second Bishop too, and/or open up the diagonal for our  c8 -Bishop with  exd5 . }
