{ Chapter 26 addresses White's alternatives on move 4 in the QGD. There aren't many options, but it makes a lot of sense for White to start with  4.Bg5  if they know that we intend to enter the Gukesh QGD. }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bg5( { The trickiest 4th move alternative. White doesn't commit to }4.cxd5 { yet, which means our c8-Bishop is closed for the moment. }4...Nbd7 { doesn't make sense for us, since after }5.e3 Bb4 { , we have a worse version of the Manhattan. } )( 4.g3 { transposes to the Catalan after }4...Be7 { . } )
4. dxc4{ We have a twist prepared here, and we won't transpose into the Vienna lines with ... Bb4 . }
5. e3{ The main move. White employs a solid strategy and wants to recapture  c4  with the Bishop. }( 5.Nf3 { White wants to transpose to QGD/Vienna with }e3 { on the next move. However, we play }5...c5 { and both  e3 / e4  transpose to the lines in this chapter. } )
5. c5{ Just like in the variation with 5.e4, we look to undermine white's centre with  c5 . }
6. Bxc4{ White recaptures the  c4  pawn, and develops a piece. }
6. cxd4{ We create an isolated pawn in the center, in return for slightly less space, and temporarily undeveloped pieces. }
7. exd4{ With a typical IQP position. White has a weak pawn on  d4  but has a 3vs1 lead in development. The main confrontation point in these positions is about activity. If Black can develop the pieces comfortably, we stand better due to the better pawn structure. White wants to restrict our development and exploit their slight lead in development. A good element in our favor is that White's Bishop is on  c4 , and not on  d3 , where it is ideally placed. }
7. Be7{ We develop our Bishop and want to finish kingside development, followed by developing the Queenside pieces. }
8. Nf3{ White quickly finishes the kingside development too. The next couple of moves are the logical castling by both sides, to safeguard their king. }
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Nc6{ The response. The Knight is best placed on  c6 , from where it exerts pressure on  d4 , as well as keeps the option of ... Nb4 - Nbd5 , occupying the outpost, alive in the future. This position is a big tabiya with several games, but the most critical seems to be  10.Re1 . }
10. Qd2{ Starting with this loses some flexibility. White's ideas in the IQP traditionally include placing the Queen on  d3 , or  d2  depending upon the situation. With  Qd2 , white commits to a plan, losing some flexibility. }
10. b6{ We don't need to waste time on  a6 - b5  and can develop the Bishop in one go with  Bb7  next. }
11. Rad1{ White brings the rook into the game }
11. Bb7{ We develop our last minor piece. Our plan is to either play  Nb4 - Nbd5  or  Na5 , based on White's response. }
12. Rfe1{ White brings the other rook too. }( 12.d5 { is a typical motif in the IQP. White wants to get rid of the weakness and claim a small edge due to the lead in development. However, we can play }12...Na5 { and white isn't able to hold the pawn on  d5  comfortably. } )
12. Na5{ with huge pressure on  c4  &  f3 . Our plans include  Bxf3 , or  Rc8 . }
