10. a6{ Not our usual response, but very important here. We would have loved to develop the  c8 -Bishop in one go with  b6 , but White has  Ne5  there which poses some of us some uncomfortable questions. With  a6 , we look to gain space with  b5 , and then play  Bb7 . This has the advantage of giving us more space, but in return, we spend an extra move on developing the Bishop. }
11. Rc1{ White develops the Rook, and brings in on to an open file. }
11. b5{ We gain space on the queenside and prepare ... Bb7 . }
12. Bd3{ The most challenging idea from a strategic viewpoint. White brings the Bishop back to where it belongs. The drawback is that White has spent some time to do so. }
12. Bb7{ We bring our Bishop out and prepare  Nb4 . The only challenging try could be }
13. Bb1{ With the intention of creating a battery with  Qd3 . We are unbothered, and bring out our Rook. }
13. Rc8
14. Qd3
14. Nb4{ White cannot really poke weaknesses on the Kingside. We are threatening ... Bxf3 - Qd4  next, or at least reserve the option of playing ... Nbd5 , with a slightly better position since we have brought out all of our pieces comfortably and have a better pawn structure. }
