10. Bd3{ White develops naturally, and brings us a piece into the game. }
10. Ng4{ Our idea. We could have castled too, but I want to create strategic imbalances and win the bishop pair. The drawback of course is that we have spent a considerable time with our knight. }
11. Qe2{ The top choice of the comp. White looks to recapture on  e3  with the queen, keeping the queenside pawn structure intact. }
11. Nxe3{ We win the bishop pair nevertheless. }
12. Qxe3{ We have the Bishop pair, while white has slightly active pieces. Our goal is to finish development while wanting to exploit their lead in development. }
12. O-O{ We finish our kingside development, and want to play  f6 - e5  next, gaining space in the center, and opening up the diagonal/file for the bishop/rook. }
13. h4{ Isn't approved by the computer, but looks very tempting. White wants to launch an attack with  h5 / Ng5  next. However, we don't need to be afraid since  Ng5  can always be met with  h6  safely. These attacks are dangerous with the dark-squared Bishops in the game, but without them, we don't need to be fearful. }
13. Qb6{ We start attacking white's weaknesses. }
14. O-O-O{ White has completed the development, and wants to start attacking, but we have the central breakthrough first. }( 14.Ng5 { doesn't lead anywhere, and we can safely play }14...h6∓ { followed by the typical  e5 . } )
14. e5{ Challenging white's center. }
15. Nxe5{ This doesn't work. }
15. Nxe5
16. dxe5
16. Qxe3{ The important intermezzo. }
17. fxe3
17. Bxe5{ We are better due to better pawn structure and pair of bishops. }
