13. Bc7{ This rare move, which has only been tried twice OTB is the best one in my opinion. Although we give up the control of the  d1 - h8  diagonal, we don't allow white to gain a tempo with  Bf6   g5 .     With ... Bc7 , we are looking to play ... e5  next, so white needs to be very concrete and play }
14. h5{ The strongest move. White wants us to open our kingside with  gxh5 , after which castling becomes a lot more riskier. }
14. gxh5{ We take the pawn, and hope that white recaptures. This weakens our kingside considerably, but allowing  h6  was a deal breaker. }
15. Rg1{ This is the most dangerous practical try, in my opinion. We need to show a very high degree of precision here. White's idea is to play  Bh6  next, and meet ... Rg8  with  gxh5 , with a deadly pin. We are forced to play the next move. }
15. hxg4
16. Qd4{ This is the most dangerous try. White threatens  Qxg7  and we cannot move our knight away due to ... Qxh8 . }
16. e5{ The only move. We shut down the pin and look to create counterplay. }
17. Nxe5{ Forced, as otherwise retain a humungous center. }
17. Nf5{ We improve our knight, and make things concrete. }
18. Bb5+{ White doesn't back down and keeps on making threats. It seems that we are losing material, but we have a spectacular move. }
18. Ke7( { Where we are surviving. }18...Kf8 { ran into }19.Ng6+ { , followed by  Qxh8 . With  ...Ke7 , we are threatening  ...Nxd4 / Nxe3 / Bxe5 , so white needs to be quick too. If we are able to exchange a few pieces, we would be better due to the extra pawn. } )
19. Bg5+{ The most concrete. White threatens to win our Queen. }
19. Ke6{ This is the real surprise. ... f6  loses to  Nc6 +, but with ... Ke6 , we reinforce the attack over the  e5 -square. We are happy to trade Queens after  Bxd8 . }
20. Qxg4{ White gets the Queen out of the attack and defends the  g5 -Bishop. }
