{ In chapter 28, we will be covering all the alternatives from move 6 to 8 in the London system. }1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. Nf6
3. e3
3. e6
4. Nf3
4. c5
5. Nbd2
5. Nc6
6. Bb5{ White decides to develop the bishop to the most active square, and threatens  Bxc6 , which spoils our pawn structure. However, this also leaves the bishop on  b5  vulnerable. }
6. Bd7{ We solidly defend the  c6 -knight with our bishop and develop a piece. }( 6...Qb6 { is a very tempting option, which tempts white to give the bishop pair with  Bxc6 . However, white has the super precise }7.c4 { with the idea of gaining space in the center and defending the bishop on  b5 . If we try to undermine white's center with }7...cxd4 8.exd4 dxc4 { , white can play the precise }9.a4! { defending the  b5 -bishop, and threatening to improve the position of the poorly placed knight with  Nc4 . } )
7. O-O{ White finishes the kingside development. }
7. Be7{ We develop our last minor piece too. Apart from ... O-O , we are also sneakily threatening ... Nh5 , winning the  bishop pair for us. }
8. dxc5{ Was tried in a few games. }
8. Bxc5
9. c4{ Challenging our central pawn on  d5 . However, we can play the simple }
9. a6{ Looking to meet  Ba4  with ... dxc4 . White needs to play  Bxc6 , which concedes the bishop pair, and gives us an easy game. }
