4. c5
5. Nbd2
5. Nc6
6. c3{ This move was covered in the previous chapter too. }
6. cxd4
7. exd4
7. Nh5{ We have covered 8.Be3 in the previous chapter, and will be covering the other options here. }
8. Bg5{ The most popular move on Lichess. White attacks our queen, and provokes  f6 . }
8. f6{ We are happy to play it though, since  f6  is an important of our plan of gaining space with  e5 . }
9. Be3
9. Bd6{ This variation is already a better version of  8.Be3  lines. We have  f7 - f6  included, which helps us achieve our plans of gaining space with  e5 . If white wanted to go for  Be3  lines, 8.Be3 is the way to go. }
10. g3{ White prevents ... Nf4 . Unlike the 8.Be3 line, we don't have the opportunity to play ... Nf6 - Ng4 . }
10. O-O{ We finish our kingside development, and look to exploit the weak white's king on  e1 . }
11. Bg2{ White fianchettos the Bishop, and prepares 0-0. This is the main move both in Lichess , & the live chess database. }
11. f5{ Looking to strike with  f4 . }
12. Ne5{ The main move. White attacks  h5 , and improves the position of the knight. However, the knight on  e5  is still somewhat vulnerable. }
12. f4{ We forget about our hanging piece and focus on counterattack! Our ideas is to meet  Qxh5  with ... fxe3 , followed by capturing on  e5 . We will then attack the weak pawns on  e5  &  e3 . We end up with a better pawn structure and, a safer king. We may retain the pair of bishops, or capture the knight on  e5  with our bishop, spoiling our opponent’s pawn structure further. }
13. Nxc6{ has been played several times too. }
13. bxc6
14. Qxh5
14. fxe3
15. fxe3{ White cannot castle anymore, and wants to play 0-0-0 next. }
15. Rb8{ We start attacking the weaknesses on the Queenside. }
16. b4{ Pretty much the only way to keep the game going.  O-O-O  was met by  g6  &  Qa5 , with a deadly attack. }( 16.Nb3 a5 { doesn't help white either. } )
16. a5{ We keep on attacking the Queenside weaknesses. }
17. a3
17. Ra8{ We are threatening ... axb4 , followed by the penetration with our a-rook. White is worse due to the inability to safeguard the king. }( 17...g6 { is the stronger move objectively, but doesn't fit in the strategic scheme of attacking the queenside weaknesses. We are not engines, and keeping the lines as consistent as we can is the best way to memorise. }18.Qe2 Ra8-+  )
