{ In this chapter, we'll be dealing with the last set of  e3 -sidelines of the London system variations. There aren't many, and most of them transpose to the main lines, but it's good to be aware of move order subtleties. Please note that Jobava London & few other sidelines are covered separately in the next chapter. }1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. Nf6
3. Nd2{ The idea of early  Nd2  is to meet  c5  with  dxc5  and  Nb3 . }
3. c5{ White wants to play  dxc5  but that doesn't mean we should be afraid of it!  dxc5  loses space in the center. }
4. dxc5{ Consistent, but inaccurate. }( 4.e3 Nc6 { and we transpose after  Nf3  or  c3 . } )
4. Nc6{ We develop a piece and are preparing to win the  c5  pawn after  e5 . }
5. Nb3{ Pretty much the only way to defend  c5 . }
5. e5{ We gain space in the center nevertheless }
6. Bg5{ White removes the Bishop from the attack, and threatens  Bxf6 . }
6. Bxc5{ We recover the pawn based on the tactical point that }
7. Nxc5
7. Qa5+
8. c3
8. Qxc5{ We are better due to more space and better developed pieces. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) London System - Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Bf4 Nf6 3.e3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
