{ In this chapter, we'll be dealing with the last set of  e3 -sidelines of the London system variations. There aren't many, and most of them transpose to the main lines, but it's good to be aware of move order subtleties. Please note that Jobava London & few other sidelines are covered separately in the next chapter. }1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. Nf6
3. e3
3. e6{ We start with  e6  to avoid all the  dxc5  lines. }
4. Nd2{ The key sideline of this chapter. White tries to delay  Nf3 . }( 4.Bd3 { starting with  Bd3  also doesn't have a great independent value. We can play the natural response. }( { ( }4.c3 c5 { will transpose to one of the previously checked lines after  Nd2 ,  Nf3  &  Bd3 ). } )4...c5 5.Nf3 ( { ( }5.c3 Nc6 6.Nd2 { transposes). } )5...Nc6 { we are threatening  ...c4-b5  next, so white needs to play the next move. }6.c3 { transposing to the previous  chapter.  } )
4. c5{ We follow our plan, and look to tranpose to the  Nf3  lines, unless white deviates. }
5. c3
5. Nc6{ still sticking to the plan. }
6. Bg3{ With the intention to transpose to the ... Bd6  lines after ... Bd6   Ngf3 . We don't want to do that, and therefore we develop the bishop. }( 6.Ngf3 cxd4 7.exd4 { we transpose to  4.Nf3   c5   5.c4  variation. } )( 6.Ngf3 { transposes to the main lines of the London system. } )
6. Be7{ We don't want to trade the bishops here, since white has already committed to  Bg3 . }
7. Ngf3{ Allows us the typical the response. }
7. Nh5{ Winning the bishop pair is our aim. We plan to play ... Nxg3 , followed by ... Qb6 - Bd7 - g6 - O-O-O  in some order. It's significant to note that we aim to castle queenside, not kingside, as after ... Nxg3 , the h-file opens for White's rook. }
