3. e6{ We stay consistent with our strategy of playing  e6 , before playing  c5 . }
4. Nbd2{ This is another try, but an inferior one. White unnecessarily shuts down the  c1 -bishop. }
4. c5{ We gain space as usual. }
5. e3{ White opens up the diagonal for the bishop. }
5. Nbd7{ Since the bishop on  c1  is blocked, we can play  Bd6  if we want to, without any problems. And if  Bd6  is not an issue, I don't want our knight to be bothered by the  Bb5  pin. The secondary advantage is that the knight on  d7  does not interfere with the diagonal of our  c8 -bishop, which is coming to  b7  next. We prevent  e4  this way. We transpose to the Colle system. }
6. Bd3{ The most active square for the bishop. }
6. b6{ We make the necessary move first, and keep the flexibility of playing ... Be7 - Bd6 . We are preparing ... Bb7  next. }
7. O-O{ White finishes the kingside development. }
7. Bb7{ We develop our Bishop. With  Bb7 , we have a greater control over the  e4  square, which prevents white's plan of playing  e4  & gaining space. }
8. Ne5{ The most ambitious move. White moves the knight to the most active square and looks to play  f4  next. }
8. Be7{ We develop our Bishop and keep the  d6  square reserved for our knight. }
9. f4{ White gets the stonewall structure in. }
9. O-O{ We finish our kingside development. }
10. Qf3{ White develops the Queen, and prepares  Qh3 , looking to assault our King. }
10. Ne8{ The key reason for playing  Be7 , & not  Bd6 . We keep the  d6  square accessible for our knight. With  Ne8 , we prepare  Nd6  and look to neutralize the kingside attack with  f5 . }
11. Qh3
11. f5{ White has no attack, and }
12. g4{ is comfortably met with }
12. Nd6{ We look to trade our worst-placed piece with  a5 - Ba6  next. }
