{ Chapter 31 deals with the Jobava London, and the remaining of white's sides in the London system. }1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. Nf6
3. Nc3{ The Jobava London. It's been way too much in fashion recently, mainly by players looking to get a playable game. We don't mind that, and in fact, appreciate it! From a strategic point of view, the knight is misplaced on  c3 , since white has played  c2 - c4  yet. However, white has some concrete ideas associated with  Nb5  &  f3 - g4 . Still, we have several ways to play against the Jobava London. I recommend one of the most logical ones. }
3. e6{ We play in the typical London style. Even though we shut down the  c8 -Bishop, we reduce the impact of  Nb5  due to the possibility of  Bb4 - Ba5 . }
4. e3{ Has been the main try, but allows us }
4. Bb4{ pinning the  b4 -knight. }
5. Bd3{ White's main try. White wants to develop the knight next, preferably to  e2 , without shutting the Bishop down. However, we can continue gaining space with }
5. c5{ Introducing the threat of  Qa5 . }
6. dxc5{ Forced. }
6. Nbd7{ We want to recapture with the knight, which improves the position of the knight significantly and attacks the Bishop on  d3 . }
7. Nf3
7. Bxc3+
8. bxc3
8. Nxc5{ Followed by  O-O . Black is better due to more space and better pawn structure. }
