[White "32) Torre Attack and 2.Bg5"]
[Black "3.Bg5 c5 4.Bxf6 gxf6 5.dxc5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3{ This is another version of the Trompowsky. }
2. Nf6
3. Bg5{ This is the delayed Trompo. White waits for us to play ... Nf6 , so that  Bg5  can threaten ... Bxf6 . The drawback is that White has committed to  Nf3 , thereby losing some flexibility. }
3. c5{ We gain space on the queenside, and challenge white's center. }
4. Bxf6{ White spoils our kingside pawn structure. In return, we secure the bishop pair and gain opportunities to increase our space. }
4. gxf6{ This allows us to push ... e5  later on. Our weaknesses on the kingside are not too significant, since White lacks the dark-squared bishop needed to attack them. }
5. dxc5{ White wins a pawn but concedes the center. }
5. Nc6{ We develop our knight first, to prevent  b4 . Our idea is to play  e5  next, gaining space and taking on  c5 . }
6. a3{ This is dubious, but it's an important move to know. White wants to play  b4  next, in order to support the  c5  pawn. }
6. e5{ We gain space as usual. }
7. b4{ White defends the pawn. }
7. Bg7{ We fianchetto the bishop and bring it to the most active square. Our plans include playing ... f5  & ... e4  at some point. }
8. e3{ White looks to complete the kingside development. }
8. O-O{ We safeguard our king and finish our kingside development. We are ready to strike in the center. }
9. Bb5
9. f5( { Preparing }10.-- 10...e4 11.Nd4 Nxd4 12.exd4 f4 { , with a kingside storm. } )
10. Bxc6{ White eliminates the attacker of the  b4 -pawn, but gives up the bishop pair. }
10. bxc6{ We have 3 strong pawns in the center while white has none. We have sufficient compensation for the pawn. We want to play ... a5  next, attacking white's weakness on  b4 . }
11. O-O{ Safeguarding the king. }
11. a5{ We start attacking the weakness. }
12. Nbd2{ The most natural, but an instructive error. }
12. e4{ We gain space and force the next reply. }
13. Nd4
13. Bxd4{ Deflecting the  e3 -pawn. }
14. exd4
14. Qf6{ This is followed by ... f4 , initiating a massive attack on the kingside. White's  g2 -pawn is particularly vulnerable, and we'll aim to exploit that. Other strategies include playing ... Kh8  & ... Rg8 , to incorporate another piece into the attack. }
