( { Chapter 33 deals with the Veresov and a few other options for white, after }1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 { . } )1. d4
1. d5
2. Nc3{ White develops their knight, and prepares to gain space with  e4 . However, we can play }
2. Nf6{ Stopping  e4 , and developing a piece. The knight on  c3  is slightly misplaced, as it in front of the white's  c2 -pawn. Nevertheless, It's still something we should be aware of. }
3. e4{ has been tried in a few games, but is a superficial sacrifice. White's idea is to meet }
3. dxe4{ Winning a pawn. }
4. f3{ This was white's idea. White wants us to take on  f3 , so that the knight comes out to  f3 , and white has a 2 vs 1 lead in development. }( 4.Bg5 { this is a possible sideline too, but we aren't bothered. We can stay consistent with our strategy and play }4...c6 { looking to play  ...Bf5/Bg4  on the next move. If white tries to win a pawn with }5.Bxf6 { we can happily recapture and play }5...exf6 { opening up the diagonal for our bishop, and winning the bishop pair. Black is already slightly better. A sample line can be }6.Nxe4 { but we can start taking over by attacking white's weaknesses by playing }6...Qb6 { where white is under huge pressure. } )
4. exf3{ We gladly accept the second pawn. We shouldn't worried about a small lead in development for our opponent. }
5. Nxf3{ White takes the pawn back and develops a piece. }
5. c6{ We take necessary precautions against  Qxb7 , after  Bg4   h3   Bxf3   Qxf3 . }( 5...Bg4 { runs into }6.h3 Bxf3 7.Qxf3 c6 8.g4± { with a strong initiative for white. } )
6. Bd3{ The bishop is less active here. We play the natural response now. }
6. Bg4{ And follow up with the natural ... e6 , ... Be7 , ... Nbd7  & ... O-O . White doesn't have enough compensation. }
