{ Chapter 34, the last one of this course, deals with all of white's setups with  e3 , without developing the  c1 -Bishop. This includes setups with & without  c4 , as well as with and without  Nf3 . }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4{ We'll not be covering the main lines, but the setups with  3.Nf3-e3  &  3.Nc3 e3 . }
2. e6
3. Nc3{ Against the  Nf3 - e3  &  Nc3 - e3  setups, I recommend the common theme of  Nf6 - a6 , with the idea of playing  dxc4  &  b5 , or playing  Bd6 . }
3. Nf6
4. e3{ White defends the  c4  pawn, but restricts the movement of the  c1 -bishop. I don't think it's the best approach strategically, since white closes down the bishop for no clear reason. That being said, white can afford to do such things, since they get half-a move extra at the beginning of the game. }
4. a6{ This move serves two purposes. Firstly, we prepare ... dxc4 - b5  in some situations. Secondly, we control  Nb5 , and thus can try to play ... b6 - Bd6 , situating the bishop on the most active square. }
5. Nf3{ White develops their kingside knight. }
5. Nbd7{ We choose the typical Manhattan setup with ... Nbd7 . Our plan is to either to play ... b6 , ... Bb7  & ... Bd6  next, placing both Bishops on the ideal diagonals. }
6. b3{ White's main setup. They want to play  Bb2  &  Bd3  next. Starting with  Bd3  would have been met with  dxc4 , followed by  b5 . }
6. b6{ We want to play  Bb7  next, and place the Bishop on the ideal square. From  b7 , our Bishops supports  d5 , as well as gets activated after some trades in the center. }
7. Bd3{ White develops their last kingside piece and looks to castle next. }
7. Bb7{ We bring out our bishop. }
8. O-O{ White finishes their kingside development. }
8. Bd6{ We bring out our final piece and prepare  O-O  on the next move. }
9. a4{ This idea is a very common idea in these positions. White wants to play  a5  next, and spoil our pawn structure on the queenside. The drawback is that this weakens the  b4 -square, and gives us a juicy outpost. }
9. O-O{ We finish our kingside development. Our idea is to play  c5  at some point next, provided doesn't have those  a5  ideas. White can't play  a5  here due to  Bb4 , with a double attack on  c3  &  a5 . }
