{ Chapter 34, the last one of this course, deals with all of white's setups with  e3 , without developing the  c1 -Bishop. This includes setups with & without  c4 , as well as with and without  Nf3 . }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4{ We'll not be covering the main lines, but the setups with  3.Nf3-e3  &  3.Nc3 e3 . }
2. e6
3. Nc3{ Against the  Nf3 - e3  &  Nc3 - e3  setups, I recommend the common theme of  Nf6 - a6 , with the idea of playing  dxc4  &  b5 , or playing  Bd6 . }
3. Nf6
4. e3{ White defends the  c4  pawn, but restricts the movement of the  c1 -bishop. I don't think it's the best approach strategically, since white closes down the bishop for no clear reason. That being said, white can afford to do such things, since they get half-a move extra at the beginning of the game. }
4. a6{ This move serves two purposes. Firstly, we prepare ... dxc4 - b5  in some situations. Secondly, we control  Nb5 , and thus can try to play ... b6 - Bd6 , situating the bishop on the most active square. }
5. Nf3{ White develops their kingside knight. }
5. Nbd7{ We choose the typical Manhattan setup with ... Nbd7 . Our plan is to either to play ... b6 , ... Bb7  & ... Bd6  next, placing both Bishops on the ideal diagonals. }
6. c5{ An interesting, but a dubious idea. White gains space on the queenside. }
6. b6{ We immediately undermine the  c -pawn. }
7. b4( { It is probably best to play }7.cxb6 { , but this is not in the spirit of the position. White gives up the space they gained with  c5 . After }7...cxb6 { , we intend to follow up with }...Bb7 { and }...Bd6 { . We can then connect the rooks with  ...Qe7  and aim for the  ...b5  push at some point. } )
7. a5{ Forcing white to make a concession on the queenside.  a3  isn't possible due to ... axb4  where white can't recapture due to the pin on the a-file. }
8. c6{ White's idea. We cannot play 8... Nb8  due to 9.b5, where our knight on  b8  is helpless, and without squares. However, we do have magnificent piece sac here. }
8. axb4
9. cxd7+
9. Bxd7
10. Nb1
10. c5{ Black has amassed powerful pawns on the queenside and holds a significant advantage. We can push ... c4  at any time, considering moves like ... Ba4 . White can't withstand the pressure exerted by these pawns, which restrict the movement of their queenside pieces. As a result, White will likely capture on  c4  when we make that move, allowing us to regain the lost material. }
11. Nbd2
11. Bd6{ Get all of our pieces developed before playing ... c4 . Only when White plays  Be2  or makes a move with the queen should we play ... c4 , in order to waste one of their moves. }
