{ Chapter 34, the last one of this course, deals with all of white's setups with  e3 , without developing the  c1 -Bishop. This includes setups with & without  c4 , as well as with and without  Nf3 . }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4{ We'll not be covering the main lines, but the setups with  3.Nf3-e3  &  3.Nc3 e3 . }
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. e3{ White shuts down the  c1 -Bishop voluntarily but prevents all of the  dxc4  ideas. I don't think that not developing a piece when it's possible to do so is a strong approach strategically. We have several reasonable plans, but I want to be consistent and try to transpose to lines that we already know, to avoid memorization for not-so-important lines. }
4. a6{ We keep our plan consistent and look to transpose after  Nc3 . }
5. Nbd2{ The main try to avoid transposition. However, the knight is slightly misplaced in the centre and doesn't challenge the center. We look to exploit this by playing }
5. c5{ and striking the center. }
6. cxd5{ White wants us to recapture with the e-pawn, which creates an isolated pawn in the center. }
6. Nxd5{ We don't want to do that! We keep our pawn structure intact, and develop normally. }
7. Be2{ White develops normally. }( 7.e4 { is comfortably met with }7...Nf6 { With a sharp position on the board, where both sides have their chances. }8.dxc5 ( { ( }8.e5 Nfd7⇆ { ) } )8...Bxc5 9.e5 Nd5⇆  )
7. cxd4{ We ask the same question to white: Do you want to create an isolated pawn in the center or recapture with the knight? }
8. Nxd4
8. e5{ We gain space and open up the diagonal for our Bishop }
9. N4f3
9. Nc6{ We have a slightly more pleasant position due to more space and the active knight on  d5 . Our plan is the routine development of Bishops, and castling. }
