{ Chapter 34, the last one of this course, deals with all of white's setups with  e3 , without developing the  c1 -Bishop. This includes setups with & without  c4 , as well as with and without  Nf3 . }1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. e3{ The big main line of this chapter. This is played by both the ambitious and club players. The ambitious players are just looking for some interesting tries, while the club players wants to just get the Colle/Zukerkort system in with  Bd3 - b3 - Bb2  in some order. }
3. c5{ We gain space in the center. This is the most ambitious system, which looks to punish the Zukerkort system with  b3 . We need to know a bit more lines, but Zukerkort is a very popular system, and I think the effort is worth it. }
4. b3{ Is the Zukerkort system. White wants to play  Bb2  next, followed by the typical plan of  Bd3 - Nbd2 -0-0. All good, but we won't allow our opponents to do that. }
4. cxd4{ This way, we avoid all of the  dxc5  tricks, and open up the c-file for our  a8  rook to target  c2  in the future. }
5. exd4{ White's main move.  Nxd4  was worse due to  e5 !, after which we keep a huge spacial edge in the center. }
5. Nc6{ We continue with our natural development. A good point of this structure is that white cannot play  c3 , since they have already committed to  b3 . This means that  Bd3  is always suspicious due to the threats of  Nb4 . }
6. Bb2{ White develops their minor piece. However, the bishop on  b2  is now bad since white can't open the  a1 - h8  diagonal with  dxc5 . }( 6.Bd3 { runs into }6...Bg4⩱ { another plan. We want to play }e6 { next, followed by }Bd6 { & }Rc8 { , with a much better Caro exchange. } )
6. Bf5{ We bring out our light-squared Bishop before playing  e6 , and keep an eye on  c2 . }
7. Bd3
7. Bxd3
8. Qxd3
8. e6{ With a slightly better position for black. We want to develop normally with  Be7 ,  O-O  &  Qb6 . The main difference between this position and the Zukertort system is that we have managed to get rid of the light-squared bishops, which significantly affects whites chances. We are left with a good Bishop for white's bad one, while the  c2 -pawn is a constant worry for white. }
