{ Chapter 34, the last one of this course, deals with all of white's setups with  e3 , without developing the  c1 -Bishop. This includes setups with & without  c4 , as well as with and without  Nf3 . }1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. e3{ The big main line of this chapter. This is played by both the ambitious and club players. The ambitious players are just looking for some interesting tries, while the club players wants to just get the Colle/Zukerkort system in with  Bd3 - b3 - Bb2  in some order. }
3. c5{ We gain space in the center. This is the most ambitious system, which looks to punish the Zukerkort system with  b3 . We need to know a bit more lines, but Zukerkort is a very popular system, and I think the effort is worth it. }
4. c4{ Is one of the weapons used by ambitious 3.  e3  players. White challenges our center, and is ready to accept an IQP position after  cxd4   exd4   dxc4   Bxc4 . There are several attempts here, but I like the most principled choice with }
4. cxd4{ We ask white to create an isolated pawn }
5. exd4
5. g6{ The most ambitious move strategically. This is one of the very few times where we fianchetto our dark-squared Bishop. With  g6 , we don't block our  c8 -Bishop, and look to place our dark-square Bishop on  g7 , from where it exerts the maximum pressure on  d4 . }
6. Nc3{ White's main move. White develops their minor piece and put pressure on  d5 . }
6. Bg7{ We develop our other kingside minor piece and are ready to castle next. We then want to play  Nc6 , followed by putting pressure on  d4  with  dxc4 , or if white plays  c5 ,  Ne4 / b6 . }
7. Qb3{ Is another ambitious attempt, forcing us to take on  c4 , so that white's Bishop is developed in one go. }
7. O-O{ We reject that and ask white to take on  d5 , claiming that we'll recover the pawn later on. }
8. cxd5{ White accepts the pawn. This is the only principled move strategically. }
8. Nbd7{ We bring out our knight, preparing  Nb6 , looking to take on  d5 . }
9. Bc4{ Defends the  d5 -pawn preemptively. }
9. Nb6{ We bring out the Knight nevertheless and prepare to take on  c4 , winning the second Bishop too. }
10. O-O{ White finishes their kingside development. }
10. Nxc4{ We win the second Bishop. }
11. Qxc4
11. b6{ Preparing ... Bb7  and looking to win the  d5 -pawn. White was a couple of ways to stop this. }
12. Ne5{ This is an interesting idea too. White looks to occupy the outpost on  c6 . }
12. Bb7
13. Nc6
13. Qd7{ Unfortunately for them, the  c6 -Knight is quite loose. Our threat is to play ... Nxd5  or ... e6  next, shaking the balance of the  c6 -Knight. }
