4. Nbd7{ We prevent all  dxc5  ideas, and develop our minor piece. Although this restricts our  c8 -Bishop, it gives us the flexiblity of playing  g6 - Bg7 . We'll get the other Bishop out via  b7 . }
5. Bd3{ White's most logical move. They develop a piece and prepare  O-O . }( 5.Nbd2 { is met by }5...g6 { white has nothing better than  Bd3 . The bishop on  e2  is considerably poorly placed. } )
5. g6{ We get our bishop out to  g7 , where it is ideally placed to put pressure on  d4 . }
6. Nbd2{ The next couple of moves are both the sides finishing kingside development. }
6. Bg7
7. O-O
7. O-O{ We have finished our development. We are slightly better due to the extra space in the center. Our plan is either ... Re8 - e5 , or ... b6 - Bb7 . }
8. e4{ This is possible but we are ready to release the central tension, since we are better developed. }
8. dxe4
9. Nxe4
9. Nxe4
10. Bxe4
10. cxd4{ Releasing the central tension completely.  cxd4  gives us an isolated pawn to play against. }
11. Nxd4
11. e5{ Gaining space in the centre. We'll play ... Nc5  or ... Qc7  next, based on white's response. We are slightly better strategically due to the extra space in the center. }
