{ Chapter 34, the last one of this course, deals with all of white's setups with  e3 , without developing the  c1 -Bishop. This includes setups with & without  c4 , as well as with and without  Nf3 . }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4{ We'll not be covering the main lines, but the setups with  3.Nf3-e3  &  3.Nc3 e3 . }
2. e6
3. Nf3{ White obviously develops a minor piece towards the centre. We don't need a very big explanation for this move. }
3. Nf6
4. e3{ White shuts down the  c1 -Bishop voluntarily but prevents all of the  dxc4  ideas. I don't think that not developing a piece when it's possible to do so is a strong approach strategically. We have several reasonable plans, but I want to be consistent and try to transpose to lines that we already know, to avoid memorization for not-so-important lines. }
4. a6{ We keep our plan consistent and look to transpose after  Nc3 . }
5. b3{ White avoids  Nc3 , and prepares  Bb2 - Nbd2 . }( 5.Nc3 { the main move, transposes. } )
5. c5{ We strike in the center due to the visible dark-squared weaknesses on the Queenside. }
6. Bb2
6. cxd4{ Preparing to meet }
7. exd4
7. Bb4+{ We develop our last kingside piece and ready to castle. }
8. Nbd2{ Nc3 would have run into  Ne4 , followed by  Qa5 . With  Nbd2 , white avoids the  Ne4  threats. However, the knight is misplaced on  d2 . }
8. dxc4{ We create a set of hanging pawns in the centre. The drawback is that we give up space. }
9. bxc4
9. O-O{ Finishing kingside development. }
10. Bd3{ White develops the last minor piece, preparing to castle next, where they remain slightly better due to somewhat extra space. We therefore play the next move now. }
10. b5{ Looking to eliminate white's space. Our plan is to play ... bxc4  next, followed by ... a5 - Ba6 . White can't win the pawn on  b5  due to lack of development. }( 11.cxb5 axb5 12.Bxb5 Ne4 13.O-O Nxd2 14.Nxd2 Qa5-+ { is deadly. } )
