1. d4
1. d5
2. e3{ Rather than aiming for a colle system, white is aiming for a stonewall with  f4 - Nf3 - c3 - Bd3  in some order. This is quite popular at the club level, but is too bad to be tested at the higher levels. I recommend playing a very simplistic setup. }
2. Nf6
3. Bd3{ Stopping ... Bf5 , and preparing  f4  next. }( 3.f4 { is quite premature. After }3...Bf5⩱ { black is already better. We are very happy to exchange the light-squared bishops, as it's our worst-placed piece in the QGD structures. }{ Our idea is to keep the  e4 -square under control, and play ... Be7 , ... O-O , ... c5 , ... Nc6 , ... Qb6  next. } )
3. c5{ Gaining space in the center. }
4. c3{ White delays  Nf3 , to keep the option of  f4  alive. }( 4.Nf3 Nc6 { followed by  ...Bg4  and pressuring the  d4 -pawn, gives us a great position. } )
4. Nc6{ We advance a piece and aim to gain space with  e5 . White's last opportunity to establish a stonewall is with... }
5. f4{ White adopts the strategy of  Nf3 - Nbd2 - Ne5 , aiming to secure a grip over the  e5 -square and thereby control the center. This is a highly ambitious strategy, but it's not without its clear flaws. White positions all the pawns on dark squares, which weakens the light squares. We can exploit this vulnerability. }
5. Bg4
6. Nf3{ This is met comfortably. }
6. e6{ Now, we have the bishop outside of the pawn chain. At the appropriate moment, after moving the  f8 -bishop and castling, we will want to play  Bf5 , aiming to exchange the light-squared bishops. After  Bxf5  ... exf5 , we will have the open e-file for our rook and excellent control over the  e4 -square. }
