16. Bxf6+{ Not the most challenging. White hands over the bishop without putting up a fight. Svidler claims that the black king might be exposed, but as Kramnik shows, that's not the case. }( 16.f3 { preparing  e4 , was the most challenging line. }16...Bxc3 { black should stop  e4 . With ... Bxc3 , black also spoils white's queenside pawn structure. }17.bxc3 Na4! 18.Nb1 Re6 { defending the  f6 -knight. Black wants to play ... Rce8 / Rb6  next. }19.e4!? { white's principled try. White looks to gain space on the queenside. }19...dxe4 20.Bxf6+ { forced, as black was threatening  Qxg5 . }20...Rxf6 21.fxe4 Rxf1+ 22.Rxf1 b5⇆ { with a tricky position on the board. White has a poor pawn structure but has more space in the center and is the better king. However, the knight on  b1  is misplaced. The position is dynamically balanced, but I would very slightly prefer white since they are going to threaten our king. } )
