{ Welcome to the final section of this course, "Typical Plans and Structures". This section is akin to the "Short & Sweet" version of the course, but instead of focusing on concrete moves, we will concentrate on plans and structures. The objective is to provide you with a catalog of the most important plans, structures, and motifs, so that even if you forget the moves, you can still deduce the correct moves by applying logic during your over-the-board (OTB) or online games.    The structure of this section, encompassing the five main setups, is bifurcated into two parts: "Typical Pawn Structures and Ideas" and "Concrete Plans". The first part elucidates the thematic plans and pawn structures of the key variations, whereas the second part explicates the vital concrete plans in sub-variations.    Moving on to how to utilize this section: It can serve as a refresher course or a preparation tool for your games when you have limited time to prepare. Do pay attention to the key plans and strive to comprehend the logic behind our moves. This will assist you in finding moves OTB, even if you don't remember the concrete details. Without further ado, let's get started! }1. --
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Plans & Structures"]
[Black "Typical Plans &  Structures: The Manhattan"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. Nbd7{ The Manhattan Variation begins here. By playing ... Nbd7 , we introduce two threats: ... dxc4  and ... Bb4 . This variation circumvents the  Qa4 + lines in the Ragozin, if black opts for 4... Bb4  instead. Let's explore the thematic plans, pawn structures, and the positioning of pieces in greater depth here.    White's  c1 -bishop is destined to move to  f4  or  g5 , while the  f1 -bishop is likely to shift to  d3 , after White plays  e3 . As black, we aim to play ... Bb4 , exerting pressure on the  c3 -knight, with either ... Ne4  or ... c5 - Qa5 . We have a somewhat misplaced bishop on  c8 , which, in most cases, would be quite content to trade. We often respond to  Bg5  with ... h6  in these positions, and retaliate against  Bh4  with the sequence ... g5 - Bg3 -... Ne4  in many scenarios.    The strategy of ... Ne4 - g5  is effective against the bishop on  f4  in some positions. Additionally, we have a plan for ... dxc4 , to counter  e4  with ... Bb4 , and  e3  with ... Nb6 . This forces White to play  Bxc4 , losing the bishop pair in the process. Since we are short on space, we are eager to challenge white's center with  c5  in most lines. This becomes even more potent if white's queen moves to  c2 . Our king is typically safest on the kingside.    In this variation, our guiding principle is to enhance the positions of our pieces swiftly and create threats. }
