4. Nbd7
5. Bg5{ White's main move. White develops a piece, and puts pressure on the  d5 -pawn. White's bishop is most actively situated here. }
5. Bb4{ We bring out our bishop and put pressure on the  c3 -knight. }
6. e3{ White opens up the path for the  f1 -bishop. }
6. c5{ We attack the center, and prepare ... Qa5 - Ne4 . This is one of the key plans for us in this variation. }
7. cxd5{ White releases the tension in the center, and forces us to create an isolated pawn. }
7. exd5{ We recapture, and again look to play ... Qa5 . }
8. Bd3{ White brings out their bishop. }
8. Qa5{ We get our queen out of the pin, and increase pressure over the  c3 -knight. }
9. Qc2{ White develops their queen and defends  c3 . }( 9.O-O { is met safely with }9...c4 10.Bc2 Bxc3 { we win the pawn, and castle next. Remember to play ... h6 , to kick the bishop away from  g5 . White wants to play  Ne5 - f4 , which weakens the  e3  pawn. We want the bishop away from  g5  so that it doesn't defend  e3 . } )
9. c4{ Gaining space. }
10. Bf5{ The only square where the bishop keeps the  e4 -square protected. }
10. O-O{ We finish our development. }
11. O-O{ White does the same. White now wants to play  e4 , making our  c4  pawn vulnerable. }
11. Re8{ We stop  e4  and increase the control over  e4 . The fight now revolves around the  e4 -square, and whether we can attack White's queenside or not. }
12. Nd2{ Preparing  e4  again }
12. g6{ We force white to take a decision with their bishop }
13. Bxd7( 13.Bh3 { white keeps the bishop pair, but we play }13...Kg7 { preparing ... Nb6 , followed by ... Bxc3 - Na4 . We want to attack white's queenside weaknesses and keep control of the  e4 -square. Our other idea is to meet  Rae1  with ... Ne4 , stopping  e4 . } )
13. Nxd7{ We have won the bishop pair but have some problems with development. Our plan is to play ... Nb6 - Bxc3 - Bd7 - Na4 - Re6 . After that, we play ... f6 / Rae8 .     The idea is simple: keep the  e4  break under control, and attack the weaknesses on the queenside. }
