13. a3{ Forcing us to give the bishop pair. }( 13.O-O f5 { we retain huge space in the center, along with the advantage of bishop pair. Our next move is ... Bd6 , hinting towards a potential kingside attack, and bringing the bishop to the best available square in the position. } )
13. Bxc3+{ Spoiling white's pawn structure. }
14. bxc3
14. Nd6{ Covering the important  c4 -square. Black now wants to play ... Be6 - O-O-O  & start the kingside assault with ... h5 - h4 . White has nothing better than  O-O .     We will then launch the pawns on kingside, or exchange the light-squared bishops with ... Bg8 - Bh7 , and try to play on the light squared weaknesses. We are not afraid of  a4 - a5 - a6 , and can safely play ... b6 . }
