8. e3{ This leads to a Carlsbad structure. I will first lay down the general guidelines of the Carlsbad structure, before explaining the concrete details of this position.     In the Carlsbad structure, White aims to play  b4 - b5  and attack our weak pawn on  c6 . We usually seek play on the kingside with ... Ne4  (when the bishop is on  e7 ). Another plan involves ... a5 - b5 , gaining space on the queenside, though you must ensure that the  c6 -pawn is not weak, White cannot access the  c5 -square, and cannot break open the position with  e4 . As black, you want to occupy the  e4 -square, and not let white play  e4  without consequences. You can allow  e4  if there are mass exchanges, and the  d4 -pawn becomes weak.     Regarding the pieces, both sides usually castle short. We are content to trade the light-squared bishop for any knight or bishop. One of our knights should be on  d6 , where it controls the  e4 -square and keeps an eye on the  c4 -square, in case white decides to play  b4 .     Returning to the position, we have a Carlsbad structure, but with a twist. White's Knight is on  d2 , which means they no longer have the option of  Ne5 . So, we play... }
8. Nf8{ Preparing to win the bishop after ... Ng6  & ... h6 . This only works here, since white has wasted time with  Nd2 . }
