1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. Bg5
5. Bb4{ Welcome to the Gukesh QGD. White has developed their bishop to an active square on  g5 , and we have done the same with ... Bb4 . Unlike the traditional QGD lines with ... Be7 , we meet white head-on, maintaining our pieces on the most active squares as well.     Our typical plan involves ... h6 - Bh4 - g5 - Bg3 - Ne4 , followed by ... h5 , thereby pressuring the bishop on  g3 .     Another plan is to put pressure on the  c3 -knight with ... c5 - Qa5 . White has additional options for  Qa4 +, which are not available in the QGD. We do not shy away from giving up the bishop pair after  a3 , as it disrupts the queenside pawn structure.     Our king remains flexible and can relocate to either flank, depending on White's strategy. We typically have a slightly subpar pawn structure, but our activity compensates for that.      Remember to keep your pieces active in this variation!  }
