5. Nc6
6. c3
6. cxd4
7. exd4
7. Nh5{ Welcome to the main position of the London System. With ... cxd4  & ... Nh5 , we've made our intentions to harass the  f4 -bishop quite clear.     Our typical plan is to meet  Be3  with ... Bd6 . Following that, we aim to play ... O-O , ... g6 , and ... f6  in some sequence. We may then reroute our knight with ... Ng7 - Nf5  and play ... e5  or ... g5 . We usually develop the  c8 -bishop with ... b6 , but it might also move to  d7 . We are always pleased to secure the bishop pair.     The pawn structure resembles an exchange Caro-Kann, but a crucial difference is that our bishop will be situated on  d6 , the most advantageous square for the bishop. White's bishop will be poorly placed on  e3 .     In addition to the plans of playing on the kingside, we might also launch a minority attack with ... b5 - b4  in some lines. }
