{ The last sub-chapter in our course covers the  e3  setups in brief. This sub-chapter is not too deep, simply because the chance of this happening OTB, is quite rare. This section doesn't have a seperate 'Typical Plans & Pawn Structures' sub-chapter. }1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. e3{ This blocks the path of the  c1 -Bishop unnecessarily. }( 3.c4 e6 4.e3 a6 { our plan is quite simple: we want to play ... Nbd7 - b6 - Bb7 - Bd6 - O-O . After that, we look to play ... Re8 - e5 . If white neglects the kingside development here, we may also consider  c5 - cxd4 - dxc4 . } )
3. c5{ We gain space, and challenge white's center. }
4. c3{ The Colle system. }( 4.Nbd2 { transposes to the Colle system after }4...Nbd7 5.c3 g6  )( 4.b3 { The Zukertort system. Our system is precisely against this. }4...cxd4 { We take on  d4 , opening up the c-file for our rook. }5.exd4 Nc6 { developing our minor piece. }6.Bb2 Bf5 { followed by ... e6 - Be7 - O-O  & ... Rc8 . The pawn on  c2  is quite weak. } )( 4.c4 { runs into }4...cxd4 5.exd4 g6 { followed by ... Bg7  & ... O-O . We want to put pressure on the  d4  pawn with ... Nc6  & ... Bg4 . } )
4. Nbd7{ We defend the  c5 -pawn, and avoid white's ideas of pin after  Bb5 . }
5. Bd3
5. g6{ We want to play  Bg7  next, followed by  O-O ,  Re8  &  e5 . Black keeps a small strategic edge due to the extra space. }
